INSERT INTO `symptoms` (`symptom_id`, `symptom_name`, `description`, `causes`, `treatment`) VALUES
(1, 'Abdominal lump', 'An abdominal lump can be related to different causes. Some people describe an abdominal lump, or mass in the abdomen, as being associated with other symptoms such as:\r\n•	burning or aching sensation,\r\n•	feeling of heaviness or weakness in the abdomen,\r\n•	a sense of pressure in the abdomen, or\r\n•	pain when coughing or straining.\r\n\r\n', '•	Obstructions\n•	Infections\n•	Scar tissue\n•	Hernias\n•	Tumors \n\nThe lump may be soft or firm and can vary in size. Some causes of abdominal lumps or swellings can be painless, while others are associated with discomfort.\n\n•	Bladder Distension\n•	Bowel Obstruction\n•	Cholecystitis\n•	Intestinal Cancer\n•	Lipoma\n•	Liver Cyst\n•	Pancreatic Pseudocyst\n•	Volvulus\n', 'The treatment for an abdominal lump will depend on the underlying cause of the lump. Abdominal lumps can be caused by a variety of factors, including hernias, tumors, cysts, abscesses, or enlarged organs.\r\n\r\nIf the abdominal lump is caused by a hernia, surgery may be necessary to repair the hernia. For tumors, the treatment may involve surgery, radiation therapy, or chemotherapy, depending on the type and stage of the tumor.\r\n\r\nIf the lump is a cyst or abscess, it may need to be drained or removed surgically. In some cases, antibiotics may also be necessary to treat an infection.\r\n\r\nIf the lump is caused by an enlarged organ, such as the liver or spleen, the underlying condition causing the enlargement will need to be treated. This may involve medication, lifestyle changes, or surgery.\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider for an evaluation and diagnosis of the abdominal lump before determining the appropriate treatment.'),
(2, 'Abdominal pain', 'Abdominal pain, also known as a stomach ache, is a symptom associated with both non-serious and serious medical issues.', 'Various causes of abdominal pain include, but are not limited to\r\n•	Indigestion after eating\r\n•	Gallstones and Gallbladder Inflammation (Cholecystitis)\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Gas\r\n•	Inflammatory Bowel Disease\r\n•	Appendicitis\r\n•	Ulcers\r\n•	Gastritis\r\n•	Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease (GERD)\r\n•	Pancreatitis\r\n•	Gastroenteritis (viral or bacterial)\r\n•	Parasite Infection\r\n•	Endometriosis\r\n•	Kidney Stones (nephrolithiasis)\r\n•	Abdominal Muscle injury\r\n•	Abdominal Hernia\r\n•	Lactose Intolerance,\r\n•	Gluten Intolerance (Celiac Disease)\r\n•	Food Poisoning\r\n•	Menstrual Cramps\r\n•	Peritonitis\r\n•	Serositis\r\n•	Ischemic Bowel Disease\r\n•	Vasculitis\r\n•	Abdominal Aneurysm\r\n•	Abdominal Organ injury from trauma\r\n•	Constipation\r\n', 'It\'s important to note that if the abdominal pain is severe or accompanied by other symptoms such as fever, vomiting, or blood in the stool, it is important to seek immediate medical attention.'),
(3, 'Acne ', 'Acne is a form of skin inflammation. It typically develops when oil (sebaceous) glands become active around the time of puberty.\r\nSigns and symptoms of acne can include:\r\n•	whiteheads (closed plugged pores),\r\n•	blackheads (open plugged pores),\r\n•	small red, tender bumps (papules), and\r\n•	pimples (pustules, which are papules with pus at their tips).\r\n\r\nIn some cases, large, solid, painful lumps may form beneath the surface of the skin (nodules) or painful, pus-filled lumps beneath the surface of the skin (cystic lesions).\r\n', '•	Overactivity of the oil glands at the base of specialized hair follicles\r\n•	Bacteria grow in this oil, causing the surrounding tissues to become inflamed if the follicle ruptures.\r\n', 'Treatment options include topical or oral medications, lifestyle changes, and procedures such as chemical peels, laser therapy, or extraction of comedones. It is important to consult with a dermatologist to determine the best treatment plan for your individual needs.'),
(4, 'Aggression', 'Aggression refers to hostile, angry, or violent behavior or thoughts. Aggression is potentially dangerous when directed at oneself or others. Sometimes, people feel experience aggression when provoked, but exaggerated or persistent aggression can be a feature of underlying emotional or medical conditions. People with dementia or brain injury due to various causes may display aggression.', '•	Alcohol or Drug Intoxication\r\n•	Delusional Disorder\r\n•	Drug or Alcohol Withdrawal\r\n•	Intoxication\r\n•	Paraphrenia\r\n•	Schizophreniform Disorder\r\n•	Wilson Disease', 'It\'s important to seek professional help for aggressive behavior, especially if it is causing harm to yourself or others. A healthcare provider or mental health professional can provide personalized recommendations for treatment.'),
(5, 'Agitation', 'Agitation can be described as a feeling of annoyance, inner tension, or restlessness. Agitation is usually perceived as a negative emotion. Many people feel agitation when provoked or when under stress at work, school, or at home. In many circumstances, agitation can be a normal reaction to stress and is not a sign of disease. It can also be a feature of certain health or emotional disorders such as anxiety disorders.\r\nDepending upon the cause of the agitation, it can be associated with other symptoms, including (but not limited to)\r\n•	worry,\r\n•	depression,\r\n•	anger,\r\n•	tension,\r\n•	grief,\r\n•	irritability, or\r\n•	nervousness.', '•	Alcohol or Drug Intoxication\r\n•	Burnout\r\n•	Delirium\r\n•	Delusional Disorder\r\n•	Liver Failure\r\n•	Oppositional Defiant Disorder\r\n•	Paraphrenia\r\n•	Postpartum Psychosis\r\n•	Psychosis\r\n•	Tay Sachs Disease\r\n•	Wilson Disease', 'It\'s important to address agitation as it can lead to further health problems if left untreated. If you or a loved one are experiencing agitation, speak to a healthcare provider or mental health professional for guidance on managing this symptom.'),
(6, 'Allergies', 'Allergies are exaggerated immune responses to environmental triggers known as allergens. Allergies are very common. One of the most common forms of allergy is allergic rhinitis (\"hay fever\"), which produces symptoms like\r\n•	nasal congestion,\r\n•	itchy and watery eyes,\r\n•	sneezing,\r\n•	stuffy or runny nose,\r\n•	scratchy or sore throat,\r\n•	throat clearing,\r\n•	cough from postnasal drip.\r\n\r\n', '•	Inappropriate or misguided reaction to foreign substances (usually harmless substances)\r\n•	Allergens are the substances that trigger allergies\r\n•	Pollens are the allergens that cause hay fever, one of the most common types of allergic reaction.\r\n', 'Treatment for allergies may include avoiding allergens, taking antihistamines or other medications to relieve symptoms, and in some cases, immunotherapy to desensitize the body to the allergen. It is important for individuals with allergies to work with their healthcare provider to develop a management plan and to carry emergency medication, such as epinephrine, in case of a severe reaction.'),
(7, 'Anemia', 'Anemia is the condition of having less than the normal number of red blood cells or less than the normal quantity of hemoglobin in the blood. The oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood is, as a result, decreased. People with anemia may experience the following symptoms and signs:\r\n•	Feel tired or lightheaded (sometimes with fainting)\r\n•	Weakness\r\n•	Fatigue easily\r\n•	Have decreased energy\r\n•	Appear pale\r\n•	Develop palpitations or rapid heart rate\r\n•	Experience shortness of breath\r\n\r\n', '•	Loss of blood from menstruation\r\n•	Gastrointestinal bleeding\r\n•	Medications, including such common drugs as aspirin and ibuprofen.\r\n\r\nAnemia in children is due mainly to\r\n•	Inadequate iron in the diet\r\n•	Medications, including such common drugs as aspirin and ibuprofen.\r\n\r\n', 'Treatment options vary depending on the underlying cause of anemia, but may include iron or vitamin supplements, blood transfusions, medications to stimulate red blood cell production, or treating the underlying disease. It is important to see a healthcare provider to determine the specific cause and treatment plan for anemia.'),
(8, 'Anal itching', 'Anal itching (pruritus ani) is due to irritation of the skin around the anus accompanied by a desire to scratch. The intensity of itching increases with moisture, pressure, and sitting. At its most intense, anal itching causes intolerable discomfort described as burning and soreness. Scratching only makes the discomfort worse. Treatment of anal itching is to shower gently without directly rubbing or irritating the skin and to clean and pat dry the anus thoroughly. Use of moist pads rather than toilet paper after bowel movements can be helpful. Local application of cortisone cream may also reduce inflammation and itching, though prolonged use of cortisone may be damaging to the skin. If anal itching is prolonged, a physician should be consulted and a search made for the cause.', '•	Insufficient cleaning\r\n•	Ingesting spicy foods\r\n•	Diarrhea\r\n•	Anal tear\r\n•	Fungal infection\r\n•	Hemorrhoids\r\n•	Pinworms\r\n•	Anal abrasion\r\n•	Anal leakage\r\n•	Incontinence\r\n•	Weeping\r\n', 'It is important to see a doctor if the itching persists or is accompanied by other symptoms such as bleeding, discharge, or pain.'),
(9, 'Ankle pain', 'The ankle joint is the meeting of the bones of the leg and the foot and is responsible for the up and down motion of the foot. In popular usage, the ankle is often considered to be the ankle joint plus the surrounding anatomic region, including the lower end of the leg and the start of the flat part of the foot. Pain in the ankle can result from inflammation or injury to any of the structures in this region, including the bones, joint space, cartilage, ligaments, tendons, or muscles.', '•	Sprains\r\n•	Injuries\r\n•	Rheumatoid arthritis\r\n•	Gout\r\n•	Osteoarthritis\r\n•	Other types of arthritis can also cause ankle pain. \r\n•	Achilles tendonitis\r\n', '•	Rest, ice, compression, and elevation (RICE) therapy for mild sprains or strains\r\n•	Physical therapy or rehabilitation exercises to help strengthen the ankle and improve range of motion\r\n•	Medications such as nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) to relieve pain and reduce inflammation\r\n•	Immobilization with a cast or brace for more severe injuries such as fractures\r\n•	Surgery in rare cases, such as for severe fractures or tendon tears.'),
(10, 'Arm pain', 'Pain in the arm can result from a number of factors. Abnormalities or injury of the skin, nerves, bones, joints, blood vessels, and soft tissues of the arm can all result in pain. Arm pain, depending on the location and cause, may be accompanied by numbness, redness, swelling, tenderness, or stiffness of the joints. Injuries or trauma to any part of the arm or shoulder, including bone fractures, joint dislocations, and muscle strains and sprains, are common causes of arm pain. Sometimes diseases that affect other organs in the body, like peripheral vascular disease or arthritis, can be the cause of pain in the arm.', 'Chest pain from myocardial infarction (heart attack) and angina pectoris that may radiate (spread) to the arm area. The pain of a heart attack can be accompanied by nausea, difficulty breathing, a sense of pressure on the chest, and other symptoms. Treatments for arm pain depend on the underlying cause.', '•	Rest and ice to reduce swelling and inflammation\r\n•	Physical therapy to improve strength and flexibility\r\n•	Medications such as pain relievers, anti-inflammatory drugs, or muscle relaxants\r\n•	Injections of corticosteroids or other medications to reduce inflammation\r\n•	Surgery, in some cases, to repair or remove damaged tissue or relieve pressure on nerves'),
(11, 'Back pain', 'There are many causes of pain in the back. \r\n\r\nSymptoms in the low back can be a result of problems in the bony lumbar spine, discs between the vertebrae, ligaments around the spine and discs, spinal cord and nerves, muscles of the low back, internal organs of the pelvis and abdomen, and the skin covering the lumbar area. \r\n\r\nPains in the upper back can also be a result of disorders of the aorta, chest tumors, and inflammation of spine.\r\n\r\nCommon causes of lower back pain include strain injury from athletics or overuse, disc herniation, kidney infection, pinched nerve in the spine, and pregnancy. Less common causes of back pain include infection of the spine, ankylosing spondylitis with lumbosacral and sacroiliac joint disease, compression fracture of a spinal vertebra, disc ligament tear (annular tear), and spinal tumor or cancer in the bone of the spine.\r\n', '•	Bleeding Into Pelvis\r\n•	Dissection of the Aorta\r\n•	Infection of the Spine or Pelvis\r\n•	Metastatic Cancer\r\n•	Virus Infections\r\n', '•	Pain relievers (NSAIDs)\r\n•	Heat or cold therapy\r\n•	Physical therapy\r\n•	Massage\r\n•	Acupuncture\r\n•	Chiropractic care\r\n•	Surgery (in severe cases)'),
(12, 'Bad breath', 'Bad breath, medically known as halitosis, is a common problem. Bad breath is usually simple and preventable. Dietary factors as well as tobacco and alcohol use may all be factors in causing bad breath. \r\n\r\nPoor oral hygiene, gum disease, tooth decay, or mouth infections can also be causes of halitosis. Infections in the lungs, sinuses, or airways can also cause bad breath due to the presence of nasal secretions that may drain into the mouth. Chronic postnasal drip, for example as occurs with sinus infections, can be a cause of bad breath. \r\n\r\nCoughing up sputum from lung infections can also cause bad breath. Dry mouth (xerostomia) can be a side effect of certain medications, increasing the tendency to develop bad breath. Certain chronic diseases that severely restrict liver or kidney function may also alter the odor of the breath. Other chronic conditions that can be associated with bad breath include diabetes and acid reflux disease.\r\n', '•	Bacterial Infections\r\n•	Dietary Factors\r\n•	Food Impaction\r\n•	Foreign Body in the Nose\r\n•	Liver Failure\r\n•	Lung Abscesses\r\n•	Medications\r\n•	Oral Abscess\r\n•	Oral Ulcers\r\n•	Periodontitis\r\n•	Poorly Fitting Dentures or Oral Appliances\r\n•	Poor Oral Hygiene\r\n•	Tooth Decay\r\n', 'Practice good oral hygiene, such as brushing twice a day, flossing daily, and using mouthwash. Scrape your tongue regularly to remove bacteria and food particles. Drink plenty of water to keep your mouth moist Chew sugarless gum or suck on sugarless hard candy to stimulate saliva production Avoid foods that can cause bad breath, such as onions and garlic Quit smoking or using other tobacco products Schedule regular dental checkups and cleanings Treat any underlying dental issues, such as gum disease or cavities If bad breath is caused by an underlying medical condition, such as sinusitis or diabetes, treating the underlying condition may help alleviate the symptom.'),
(13, 'Bent penis', 'A bent penis, also known as Peyronie\'s disease, is a condition in which the penis curves or bends during an erection. The curve can be upward, downward, or to either side, and may be mild or severe. The cause of Peyronie\'s disease is not fully understood, but it is believed to involve the buildup of scar tissue in the penis. This can lead to pain during erections, difficulty achieving or maintaining an erection, and in severe cases, the inability to have intercourse. If you are concerned about a bent penis, it is important to speak with a healthcare provider for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment options.', '•	Build-up of plaque or scar tissue in the penis\r\n•	Genetics\r\n•	Side effect of certain medications or an underlying autoimmune disorder\r\n', 'It\'s important to note that not all cases of a bent penis require treatment. Mild curvature that does not cause pain or affect sexual function may not need to be corrected. However, if a bent penis is causing pain or making sex difficult or impossible, it\'s important to speak with a healthcare provider to discuss treatment options.'),
(14, 'Bleeding after vaginal sex', 'Bleeding after vaginal sex, also known as postcoital bleeding, is a common problem that can occur in women of all ages. It is often caused by minor trauma to the vaginal tissues during sex, such as rough penetration or lack of lubrication. In some cases, bleeding may also be caused by infections, such as yeast or bacterial vaginosis, or inflammation of the cervix or vagina. Cervical polyps, which are small growths on the cervix, may also cause bleeding after sex. Rarely, postcoital bleeding can be a sign of a more serious condition, such as cervical cancer or pelvic inflammatory disease. If you experience bleeding after sex, it is important to speak with your healthcare provider for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment options.', '•	Trauma\r\n•	Infections\r\n•	Cervical polyps\r\n•	Cervical or vaginal inflammation\r\n•	Sexually transmitted infections (STIs)\r\n•	Hormonal changes\r\n•	Cervical cancer\r\n', 'It is important to see a healthcare provider if you experience bleeding after sex to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.'),
(15, 'Blood clots', 'Blood clotting is a normal process that prevents loss of blood. However, sometimes disorders of the clotting system or injuries cause blood clots to form when they are not needed. In this case, the clots may cause significant complications. Blood clots can form in the veins (blood vessels that return blood to the heart after oxygen has been used by the tissues) and in the arteries (blood vessels that carry oxygenated blood from the heart to all parts of the body). ', '•	Damage or injury\r\n•	Deficiencies of blood clotting factors\r\n•	Blood diseases that affect the way blood clots\r\n•	Medications\r\n•	Surgical procedures\r\n•	Blood clotting disorders\r\n•	High blood pressure\r\n•	Diabetes\r\n', '•	Blood thinners, also known as anticoagulants, which can prevent the formation of new clots and prevent existing clots from getting larger.\r\n•	Thrombolytics, or clot-busting drugs, which are used to dissolve blood clots that have already formed.\r\n•	Invasive procedures, such as surgery or catheter-directed thrombolysis, to remove or break up the clot.\r\n•	Compression stockings or intermittent pneumatic compression devices to improve blood flow in the legs and prevent clots from forming.'),
(16, 'Blood in semen', 'Blood in semen (ejaculate) is also called hematospermia. Blood in semen can be caused by many conditions affecting the tubes that distribute semen from the testicles (seminal vesicles) or the prostate gland. The most common cause of blood in semen is inflammation of the seminal vesicles or prostate gland. Blood in the semen can temporarily be caused by injury to the prostate gland, such as from prostate biopsy.', '•	Bleeding Disorders\r\n•	Cancer of the Seminal Vesicle (Rare)\r\n•	Cyst of Urethra\r\n•	Cysts of the Seminal Vesicle or Prostate\r\n•	Echinococcus\r\n•	Prostate Biopsy\r\n•	Prostate Stones\r\n•	Prostate Telangiectasia (Widened Capillaries)\r\n•	Prostate Varices (Widened Veins)\r\n•	Trauma\r\n•	Urethritis', 'Treatment for blood in semen will depend on the underlying cause. In some cases, no treatment may be needed and the condition will resolve on its own. However, if an infection or inflammation is present, antibiotics or anti-inflammatory medications may be prescribed. If a tumor is suspected, further tests may be needed to determine the best course of treatment. If the condition is related to a blood clotting disorder, medication or other treatments may be recommended. It\'s important to see a doctor if you experience blood in semen to determine the underlying cause and receive appropriate treatment.•	Prostate enlargement or inflammation (prostatitis)\n•	Sexually transmitted infections (STIs)\n•	Cancer of the prostate, bladder, or testicles\n•	Blood disorders such as leukemia or sickle cell anemia'),
(17, 'Blood in the urine', 'Blood in the urine may or may not be accompanied by pain, but it is always abnormal and should be further investigated by a health care professional. Painful blood in the urine can be caused by a number of disorders, including stones and infections in the urinary tract. Painless blood in the urine can also be due to many causes, including cancer. Blood in the urine is also referred to as hematuria. Visible blood in the urine is referred to as gross hematuria, while blood in the urine that is not visible to the naked eye is referred to as microscopic hematuria.', '•	Glomerulonephritis\r\n•	Goodpasture\'s Syndrome\r\n•	Medications (Both Prescription and Nonprescription)\r\n•	Trauma', 'The treatment for blood in the urine will depend on the underlying cause. Here are some possible treatments:\r\n\r\n•	Antibiotics for urinary tract infections\r\n•	Pain medication and fluids for kidney stones\r\n•	Surgery to remove tumors or kidney stones\r\n•	Radiation or chemotherapy for cancer\r\n•	Blood transfusions for blood disorders\r\n•	Rest and pain medication for trauma or injury to the urinary tract.\r\n\r\nIt\'s important to see a doctor if you experience blood in the urine, as it can be a sign of a serious medical condition.'),
(18, 'Bloody Nose', 'The nose is a part of the body that is very rich in blood vessels (vascular) and is situated in a vulnerable position on the face. As a result, any trauma to the face can cause a bloody nose, and bleeding may be profuse. Nosebleeds can occur spontaneously when the nasal membranes dry out, crust, and crack, as is common in dry climates, or during the winter months when the air is dry and warm from household heaters.', '•	Bleeding Disorders\r\n•	Dry Air\r\n•	Medications (Both Prescription and Nonprescription)\r\n•	Rare Tumors Involving Nasal Passages\r\n•	Trauma', '•	Pinch the nostrils together and breathe through the mouth for 5-10 minutes\r\n•	Apply an ice pack or cold compress to the nose\r\n•	Avoid blowing or picking the nose for several hours after the bleeding stops\r\n•	Use a saline nasal spray to keep the nasal passages moist\r\n•	Apply a thin layer of petroleum jelly or antibiotic ointment inside the nostrils to prevent dryness\r\n•	Use a humidifier to add moisture to the air\r\n•	Seek medical attention if the bleeding persists for more than 20 minutes or is excessive, or if it is accompanied by dizziness, fainting, or difficulty breathing.'),
(19, 'Blurred vision', 'Blurred vision refers to a lack of sharpness of vision resulting in the inability to see fine detail. Blurred vision may result from abnormalities such as nearsightedness, farsightedness, presbyopia, or astigmatism that can be improved with corrective lenses (eyeglasses) or it may signal the presence of eye disease. Blurry vision may be experienced in one eye or in both eyes, depending upon the cause.', '•	Bleeding Into the Eye\r\n•	Convergence Insufficiency\r\n•	Corneal Abrasion\r\n•	Eye Infection\r\n•	Foreign Body in the Eye\r\n•	Incorrect Eyeglass Prescription\r\n•	Lens Dislocation\r\n•	Medications\r\n•	Trauma to the Eye or Head', '•	Refractive errors such as nearsightedness, farsightedness, or astigmatism\r\n•	Cataracts\r\n•	Glaucoma\r\n•	Macular degeneration\r\n•	Diabetic retinopathy\r\n•	Retinal detachment\r\n•	Optic neuritis\r\n•	Stroke or brain tumor'),
(20, 'Body aches or pains', 'A number of conditions can cause pain or discomfort in the body along with chills. Degenerative disc disease, muscle strain, low back strain, and cauda equina syndrome are causes of back pain. If an infection is also present, chills can occur along with fever. Many other conditions can cause body discomfort along with fever and chills, and your doctor can help you determine the cause. If you are concerned about your symptoms, seek the advice of your doctor.', '•	Physical overexertion or injury\r\n•	Poor posture or ergonomics\r\n•	Stress or anxiety\r\n•	Certain medications or drug side effects\r\n•	Inflammatory conditions such as arthritis or fibromyalgia\r\n•	Infections such as the flu or viral illnesses\r\n•	Chronic conditions such as back pain or neuropathy\r\n•	Autoimmune diseases', 'The treatment of body aches or pains depends on the underlying cause. Treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain relievers, such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen.\r\n•	Prescription medications, such as muscle relaxants or opioids.\r\n•	Physical therapy or exercise.\r\n•	Heat or ice therapy.\r\n•	Massage therapy.\r\n•	Lifestyle changes, such as reducing stress or improving sleep habits.\r\n•	Treating any underlying medical conditions.\r\n•	In some cases, surgery may be necessary.'),
(21, 'Breast Discharge', 'Breast discharge is the spontaneous flow of fluid from the nipple at any time other than during nursing.', '•	False Pregnancy (Pseudocyesis)\r\n•	Medications\r\n•	Overexercise\r\n•	Trauma', 'The treatment for breast discharge depends on the underlying cause. Some cases may require no treatment, while others may require medication or surgery. It is important to consult a healthcare provider if you experience breast discharge to determine the cause and appropriate treatment.'),
(22, 'Breast Lumps', 'Breast lumps are localized swellings, knots, bumps, bulges, or protuberances in the breast. Breast lumps may appear in both sexes at all ages. In women, the fear is usually of breast cancer, but fortunately many breast lumps turn out to be due to benign conditions that can be successfully treated', '•	Breast Cyst\r\n•	Fibroadenomas\r\n•	Infections\r\n•	Injuries by Trauma', '•	Observation and monitoring\n•	Medications such as pain relievers, hormone therapy, and antibiotics\n•	Fine needle aspiration, core needle biopsy, or surgical biopsy to remove the lump for further testing and diagnosis\n•	Surgery to remove the lump or the entire breast (mastectomy) if cancer is present\n•	Radiation therapy and chemotherapy for cancer treatment.'),
(23, 'Breast pain', 'The most common cause of breast discomfort is from the effects of hormones on breast tissue from the female menstrual period. Many women experience mild monthly breast pain in conjunction with their periods (menses). For some women, however, the pain can be more severe. This premenstrual breast pain is referred to as cyclic breast discomfort. The exact cause of cyclic breast discomfort has not been determined.\r\n\r\nMuch less common causes of breast pain include benign growths (tumors) in the breasts (including cysts), breast cancer, and certain medications. It should be noted that breast cancers are often painless and can be detected by manual examination, mammogram, or ultrasound of the breast. Breast pain is called mastodynia, mastalgia, or mammalgia by physicians.', '•	Benign Breast Tumors\r\n•	Cyclic Breast Discomfort\r\n•	Breast Cyst\r\n•	Breast Infection (Abscess and Mastitis)\r\n•	Malignant Breast Tumors\r\n•	Medications\r\n•	Plugged Milk Duct\r\n•	Thrombophlebitis (Mondor Disease)\r\n•	Trauma', 'Cyclical breast pain:\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain relievers such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen\r\n•	Reducing caffeine intake\r\n•	Wearing a supportive bra\r\n•	Heat or ice therapy\r\n•	Hormonal birth control\r\n\r\nNoncyclical breast pain:\r\n•	Treatment of the underlying cause, such as antibiotics for infections or anti-inflammatory medication for inflammation\r\n•	Pain relievers such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen\r\n•	Wearing a supportive bra\r\n•	Heat or ice therapy\r\n•	Surgery (rarely, for severe cases)'),
(24, 'Chest pain', 'Chest pain refers to discomfort, tightness, or pressure in the chest area that can range from mild to severe. The pain may be sharp or dull and may radiate to the neck, jaw, back, or arms. Chest pain can be a sign of various medical conditions, some of which are life-threatening.', '•	Heart-related issues such as angina or a heart attack\r\n•	Gastrointestinal issues such as acid reflux, peptic ulcers, or gallbladder disease\r\n•	Lung-related issues such as pneumonia or a collapsed lung\r\n•	Musculoskeletal issues such as costochondritis or a rib fracture\r\n•	Anxiety or panic attacks\r\n•	Shingles or other viral infections', 'It is important to seek medical attention if you experience persistent or severe chest pain, especially if it is accompanied by other symptoms such as shortness of breath, sweating, or dizziness.'),
(25, 'Chapped lips', 'Chapped lips refer to dry, cracked, or sore lips that can be caused by a variety of factors, including environmental conditions, dehydration, and certain medical conditions. The lips are particularly vulnerable to drying out because they lack oil glands and are constantly exposed to the elements.', '•	Exposure to cold, dry, or windy weather\r\n•	Dehydration or lack of moisture\r\n•	Licking or biting the lips\r\n•	Allergic reactions to certain products or foods\r\n•	Vitamin deficiencies, particularly vitamin B2 (riboflavin)\r\n•	Certain medical conditions, such as eczema or psoriasis\r\n•	Side effects of certain medications, such as retinoids or chemotherapy drugs', 'Chapped lips can usually be treated with home remedies such as applying a moisturizing lip balm or using a humidifier to add moisture to the air. In severe cases or if the condition is caused by an underlying medical condition, a doctor may prescribe medication or recommend other treatments. It is also important to drink plenty of water and avoid licking or biting the lips, as this can make the condition worse.'),
(26, 'Chest tightness', 'Tightness in the chest is a feeling of pressure or discomfort in the chest area that can be caused by a variety of factors. It can range from mild to severe and may be accompanied by other symptoms such as shortness of breath, dizziness, or sweating. Tightness in the chest can be a sign of a serious medical condition and should be evaluated by a healthcare provider if it persists or is accompanied by other symptoms.', '•	Heart-related issues such as angina, heart attack, or heart failure\r\n•	Respiratory issues such as asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\r\n•	Gastrointestinal issues such as acid reflux or peptic ulcers\r\n•	Panic attacks or anxiety\r\n•	Muscle strain or injury\r\n•	Rib or sternum issues such as fractures or inflammation\r\n•	Viral infections such as the common cold or flu', 'If tightness in the chest is accompanied by other symptoms such as shortness of breath, dizziness, or sweating, it may be a sign of a serious medical condition such as a heart attack and immediate medical attention should be sought. Treatment for tightness in the chest depends on the underlying cause and may include medication, lifestyle changes, or surgical interventions. Treatment for tightness in the chest depends on the underlying cause and may include medication, lifestyle changes, or surgical interventions.'),
(27, 'Chronic pain', 'Chronic pain is a persistent or recurrent pain that lasts for more than three to six months. It can affect any part of the body and can range from mild to severe. Chronic pain can be caused by a variety of factors, including injury, inflammation, nerve damage, or an underlying medical condition. It can also be accompanied by other symptoms such as fatigue, depression, and anxiety.', '•	Injury or trauma\r\n•	Inflammation due to conditions such as arthritis or autoimmune disorders\r\n•	Nerve damage due to conditions such as diabetes or multiple sclerosis\r\n•	Chronic infections such as HIV or hepatitis\r\n•	Chronic headaches such as migraines or tension headaches\r\n•	Fibromyalgia or chronic fatigue syndrome\r\n•	Cancer or cancer treatments\r\n•	Surgery or other medical procedures\r\n•	Psychological factors such as stress, anxiety, or depression', 'Treatment for chronic pain typically involves a combination of medication, physical therapy, and lifestyle changes. Pain management techniques such as acupuncture, massage, or cognitive-behavioral therapy may also be helpful. In some cases, surgery or other medical procedures may be necessary. The goal of treatment is to reduce pain, improve function, and enhance quality of life.'),
(28, 'Cloudy Urine', 'Cloudy urine refers to urine that appears cloudy or hazy rather than clear. It can be caused by a variety of factors, ranging from harmless to potentially serious medical conditions. In most cases, cloudy urine is a temporary symptom that will resolve on its own or with simple treatment.', '•	Dehydration\r\n•	Urinary tract infections (UTIs)\r\n•	Sexually transmitted infections (STIs)\r\n•	Kidney stones\r\n•	Prostatitis (inflammation of the prostate gland)\r\n•	Certain medications, vitamins, or supplements\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Diabetes\r\n•	Liver or kidney disease\r\n•	Bladder cancer', 'Treatment for cloudy urine depends on the underlying cause. In most cases, increasing fluid intake can help to flush out bacteria or other irritants and clear up the cloudiness. Antibiotics may be prescribed to treat UTIs or STIs, and pain medication may be recommended for kidney stones. Lifestyle changes such as avoiding certain foods or beverages may also be recommended. If cloudy urine is accompanied by other symptoms such as pain, fever, or difficulty urinating, it is important to seek medical attention promptly.'),
(29, 'Cluster headaches', 'Cluster headaches are a rare but extremely painful type of headache that occur in cycles, often referred to as \"clusters.\" These headaches are characterized by intense, sharp pain that typically occurs on one side of the head and is often accompanied by other symptoms such as eye watering, nasal congestion, and restlessness. Cluster headaches are more common in men and tend to begin in early adulthood.', '•	The exact cause of cluster headaches is not known, but it is believed to involve an abnormality in the hypothalamus, a part of the brain that regulates circadian rhythms and other bodily functions.\r\n•	Certain triggers may also contribute to the onset of cluster headaches, including alcohol consumption, smoking, and exposure to high altitudes.', 'Treatment for cluster headaches typically involves a combination of medication and lifestyle changes. Pain medication such as triptans or oxygen therapy can help to alleviate the acute pain of a cluster headache. Preventive medications such as verapamil or lithium may also be prescribed to reduce the frequency and severity of cluster headache cycles. Lifestyle changes such as avoiding triggers and adopting good sleep habits may also be helpful. In some cases, surgery may be recommended to treat underlying structural abnormalities in the head or neck that may be contributing to cluster headaches.'),
(30, 'Coated tongue', 'A coated tongue is a condition in which the tongue appears to be covered in a whitish or yellowish film or coating. This coating may be thick or thin and can be caused by a variety of factors, ranging from benign to more serious medical conditions. In most cases, a coated tongue is not a cause for concern and can be easily treated.', '•	Poor oral hygiene\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Mouth breathing\r\n•	Smoking or tobacco use\r\n•	Certain medications, including antibiotics and steroid inhalers\r\n•	Nutritional deficiencies, such as a lack of vitamin B12 or iron\r\n•	Fungal infections, such as thrush\r\n•	Bacterial infections, such as strep throat\r\n•	Gastrointestinal disorders, such as acid reflux or irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)\r\n•	Autoimmune disorders, such as oral lichen planus or pemphigus vulgaris', 'Treatment for a coated tongue typically involves addressing the underlying cause. This may include improving oral hygiene practices such as brushing the tongue or using a tongue scraper, increasing fluid intake to prevent dehydration, or treating infections with medication. Nutritional deficiencies can be addressed by incorporating more nutrient-rich foods into the diet or taking supplements. In some cases, a coated tongue may be a symptom of a more serious medical condition, and prompt medical attention may be necessary.'),
(31, 'Cold feet', 'Cold feet is a condition in which the feet feel unusually cold to the touch, and can be accompanied by a numb or tingling sensation. This condition is generally not a cause for concern, but can be indicative of underlying health issues in some cases.', '•	Poor circulation, often due to peripheral artery disease (PAD)\r\n•	Raynaud\'s disease, a condition that causes blood vessels to narrow and restrict blood flow to the extremities\r\n•	Hypothyroidism, a condition in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones\r\n•	Anemia, a condition in which the body does not produce enough red blood cells\r\n•	Diabetes, which can cause damage to blood vessels and nerves that affect circulation\r\n•	Chronic kidney disease, which can lead to fluid retention and decreased blood flow to the feet', 'Treatment for cold feet depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, lifestyle changes such as wearing warmer socks or using foot warmers may be helpful. Increasing physical activity and maintaining a healthy weight can also improve circulation. In cases where a medical condition is causing cold feet, treating the underlying condition may be necessary. Medications to improve circulation or manage underlying health conditions may be prescribed by a healthcare provider. In severe cases, surgical interventions may be necessary to improve circulation in the feet.'),
(32, 'Cold hands', 'Cold hands are a condition in which the hands feel unusually cold to the touch, and can be accompanied by a numb or tingling sensation. This condition is generally not a cause for concern, but can be indicative of underlying health issues in some cases.', '•	Poor circulation, often due to peripheral artery disease (PAD)\r\n•	Raynaud\'s disease, a condition that causes blood vessels to narrow and restrict blood flow to the extremities\r\n•	Hypothyroidism, a condition in which the thyroid gland does not produce enough hormones\r\n•	Anemia, a condition in which the body does not produce enough red blood cells\r\n•	Diabetes, which can cause damage to blood vessels and nerves that affect circulation\r\nChronic kidney disease, which can lead to fluid retention and decreased blood flow to the hands', 'Treatment for cold hands depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, lifestyle changes such as wearing gloves or mittens, and keeping the hands warm may be helpful. Increasing physical activity and maintaining a healthy weight can also improve circulation. In cases where a medical condition is causing cold hands, treating the underlying condition may be necessary. Medications to improve circulation or manage underlying health conditions may be prescribed by a healthcare provider. In severe cases, surgical interventions may be necessary to improve circulation in the hands.'),
(33, 'Constipation', 'Constipation is a common digestive issue in which a person experiences difficulty or infrequent bowel movements. It is characterized by the inability to pass stools regularly or easily, leading to discomfort, bloating, and abdominal pain. While it is a temporary condition for most people, chronic constipation can be indicative of underlying health problems.', '•	Lack of fiber in the diet\r\n•	Inadequate fluid intake\r\n•	Lack of physical activity\r\n•	Ignoring the urge to defecate\r\n•	Certain medications, such as opioids, antacids, and antidepressants\r\n•	Medical conditions, such as irritable bowel syndrome (IBS), hypothyroidism, and Parkinson\'s disease', 'Treatment for constipation often begins with lifestyle changes such as increasing fiber intake through diet, drinking more water, and increasing physical activity. Over-the-counter laxatives, stool softeners, and enemas may also be used to relieve constipation. In cases where medical conditions are causing constipation, treatment of the underlying condition may be necessary. A healthcare provider may recommend prescription medications or refer a patient to a specialist for further evaluation and treatment. In rare cases, surgery may be necessary to correct bowel problems that are causing chronic constipation.'),
(34, 'Cough', 'A cough is a reflex action that helps to clear the airways of mucus, irritants, or foreign substances. It is a common symptom of respiratory infections such as colds, flu, and bronchitis, but can also be indicative of other health issues.', '•	Respiratory infections such as the common cold, flu, and bronchitis\r\n•	Allergies\r\n•	Acid reflux disease\r\n•	Smoking or exposure to secondhand smoke\r\n•	Lung diseases such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\r\n•	Certain medications, such as ACE inhibitors used to treat high blood pressure\r\n•	Lung cancer', 'Treatment for cough depends on the underlying cause. For coughs caused by respiratory infections, over-the-counter cough medicines, humidifiers, and staying hydrated may be helpful in relieving symptoms. Allergy medications, acid reflux treatments, and quitting smoking can also help relieve cough symptoms. In cases where cough is caused by lung diseases such as asthma and COPD, medications and inhalers may be prescribed by a healthcare provider. If cough is indicative of lung cancer, prompt medical evaluation and treatment are essential.'),
(35, 'Curved spine', 'Curved spine, also known as scoliosis, is a medical condition in which the spine curves sideways. It can occur at any age, but is most commonly diagnosed during childhood or adolescence. While some cases of scoliosis are mild and do not require treatment, more severe cases can cause pain, breathing difficulties, and other health problems.', '•	Idiopathic scoliosis (unknown cause), which is the most common form\r\n•	Neuromuscular conditions such as cerebral palsy or muscular dystrophy\r\n•	Congenital scoliosis, which is present at birth due to abnormal spinal development\r\n•	Degenerative scoliosis, which can occur in older adults due to age-related changes in the spine', 'Treatment for curved spine depends on the severity of the curvature and the age of the patient. Mild cases may not require treatment but may need to be monitored periodically by a healthcare provider. In more severe cases, bracing or surgery may be necessary to correct the curvature and prevent further progression. Physical therapy and exercises may also be recommended to improve spinal flexibility and muscle strength.'),
(36, 'Dark colored urine', 'Dark urine is a symptom that refers to urine that is darker in color than normal. It can range in color from amber to brown to even black. Dark urine can be caused by a variety of factors, and while it is not always a sign of a serious underlying condition, it can sometimes indicate an issue that requires medical attention.', '•	Dehydration, which can concentrate the urine and make it appear darker\r\n•	Certain medications, such as those used to treat malaria or some antibiotics\r\n•	Liver diseases such as hepatitis or cirrhosis\r\n•	Hemolytic anemia, a condition in which the body destroys red blood cells too quickly\r\n•	Rhabdomyolysis, a breakdown of muscle tissue that releases a pigment called myoglobin into the urine, making it appear dark', 'Treatment for dark urine depends on the underlying cause. In cases of dehydration, drinking more fluids can help lighten the color of the urine. For liver diseases, treating the underlying condition may help resolve dark urine. In more severe cases, such as hemolytic anemia or rhabdomyolysis, hospitalization and treatment may be necessary to prevent further complications. It is important to consult a healthcare provider if dark urine is persistent or accompanied by other symptoms such as pain, fever, or yellowing of the skin and eyes.'),
(37, 'Decreased appetite', 'Decreased appetite, also known as loss of appetite or anorexia, is a symptom that refers to a lack of desire to eat or a reduced appetite. While it is normal to experience changes in appetite from time to time, persistent or severe loss of appetite can be a sign of an underlying condition.', '•	Illnesses such as the flu or a cold\r\n•	Medications, such as those used to treat depression or chemotherapy\r\n•	Chronic conditions such as liver disease, kidney failure, or cancer\r\n•	Mental health conditions such as anxiety or depression\r\n•	Aging, which can lead to a decrease in appetite', 'Treatment for decreased appetite depends on the underlying cause. For example, treating an underlying illness or adjusting medication dosages may help to improve appetite. In some cases, nutritional supplements or medications that stimulate appetite may be prescribed. For those with mental health conditions contributing to their decreased appetite, therapy or counseling may be helpful. It is important to consult a healthcare provider if decreased appetite persists or is accompanied by other symptoms such as weight loss or fatigue.'),
(38, 'Dehydration', 'Dehydration is a condition that occurs when the body loses more fluid than it takes in, resulting in an insufficient amount of water in the body\'s tissues. This can occur due to a variety of factors, such as not drinking enough fluids, excessive sweating, or vomiting.', '•	Not drinking enough fluids\r\n•	Excessive sweating due to exercise, hot weather, or fever\r\n•	Vomiting or diarrhea\r\n•	Certain medications, such as diuretics or laxatives\r\n•	Chronic conditions such as diabetes or kidney disease', 'Treatment for dehydration involves replenishing the body\'s fluids and electrolytes. This can be achieved through drinking fluids such as water, sports drinks, or oral rehydration solutions. In severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary to receive fluids intravenously. It is important to seek medical attention if dehydration is severe or persistent, as it can lead to serious complications.'),
(39, 'Delusions ', 'Delusions are false beliefs that persist despite evidence to the contrary. They are a symptom of a variety of mental health conditions, including schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and delusional disorder.', '•	Mental health conditions such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, or delusional disorder\r\n•	Substance use, particularly with stimulants such as methamphetamine or cocaine\r\n•	Sleep deprivation or other physical health conditions such as infections or neurological disorders', 'Treatment for delusions usually involves a combination of medication and therapy. Antipsychotic medications can help reduce the severity of delusions, while therapy can help individuals develop coping strategies and improve their overall mental health. In some cases, hospitalization may be necessary to ensure safety and provide intensive treatment. It is important for individuals experiencing delusions to seek professional help and support from mental health professionals.'),
(40, 'Depigmentation of skin', 'Depigmentation of the skin refers to the loss of color or pigment from the skin, resulting in patches of white or lighter-colored skin. This can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetic conditions, autoimmune disorders, and environmental factors.', '•	Genetic conditions such as albinism or vitiligo\r\n•	Autoimmune disorders such as psoriasis or lupus\r\n•	Environmental factors such as exposure to chemicals or radiation\r\n•	Infections such as leprosy or tinea versicolor\\\r\n\r\nDepigmentation can occur in small patches or may affect larger areas of the body. The affected areas may be more susceptible to sunburn and other skin damage. While depigmentation itself is not harmful, it can be a cosmetic concern and may cause emotional distress for some individuals.', 'Treatment options for depigmentation depend on the underlying cause. In some cases, such as with vitiligo, treatment may focus on restoring color to the affected areas using medications or light therapy. In other cases, such as with albinism, treatment may focus on protecting the skin from damage and preventing other associated health problems. It is important to seek medical attention for depigmentation of the skin to identify the underlying cause and develop an appropriate treatment plan.'),
(41, 'Diarrhea ', 'Diarrhea refers to loose or watery stools that occur more frequently than normal. It is a common symptom of gastrointestinal distress and can be caused by a variety of factors, including viral or bacterial infections, food intolerances, medication side effects, and underlying medical conditions.', '•	Viral or bacterial infections such as gastroenteritis or traveler\'s diarrhea\r\n•	Food intolerances such as lactose intolerance or celiac disease\r\n•	Medication side effects such as antibiotics or laxatives\r\n•	Underlying medical conditions such as inflammatory bowel disease or irritable bowel syndrome\r\n\r\nDiarrhea can cause dehydration if it is severe or prolonged, especially in young children or the elderly. Symptoms of dehydration may include thirst, fatigue, dry mouth, and decreased urine output. Treatment for diarrhea depends on the underlying cause and may include over-the-counter medications, dietary changes, or prescription medications.', 'Treatment for diarrhea depends on the underlying cause and may include over-the-counter medications, dietary changes, or prescription medications.\r\n\r\nIf diarrhea is severe or accompanied by other symptoms such as blood in the stool, fever, or severe abdominal pain, it is important to seek medical attention. These symptoms may indicate a more serious underlying condition that requires prompt treatment.');
