(70, 'Flushed skin', 'Flushed skin refers to skin that appears red, warm, and possibly swollen. It can occur due to a variety of reasons, including physiological responses, infections, medical conditions, and environmental factors.', '•	Emotional stress or anxiety\r\n•	Physical exertion\r\n•	Alcohol consumption\r\n•	Allergic reactions\r\n•	Infections, such as fever, flu, or common cold\r\n•	Hormonal changes, such as during menopause or pregnancy\r\n•	Certain medical conditions, such as rosacea or lupus\r\n•	Environmental factors, such as exposure to heat, cold, or sun', 'Treatment for flushed skin depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, no treatment is needed, as the flushing may be a temporary and harmless response. However, if the flushing is persistent, accompanied by other symptoms, or related to an underlying medical condition, medical attention may be necessary.\r\n\r\nSome general treatment options for flushed skin include:\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding triggers, such as spicy foods, alcohol, or hot environments\r\n•	Cooling the skin with a damp cloth or cool water\r\n•	Taking over-the-counter anti-inflammatory medications, such as ibuprofen or aspirin, to reduce inflammation and redness\r\n•	Applying soothing creams or lotions, such as aloe vera or calamine lotion, to calm the skin\r\n•	In severe cases or those related to underlying medical conditions, prescription medications may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider if the flushing is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, rash, or difficulty breathing.'),
(71, 'Foot pain', 'Foot pain is a common problem that can be caused by a variety of factors, including injuries, medical conditions, and overuse. The pain can be felt in various parts of the foot, such as the heel, arch, toes, or sole.', '•	Injuries such as sprains, strains, fractures, and contusions\r\n•	Medical conditions such as plantar fasciitis, bunions, flat feet, or arthritis\r\n•	Overuse or repetitive strain, such as from running or standing for long periods of time\r\n•	Ill-fitting shoes, such as high heels or shoes that are too tight or too loose\r\n•	Nerve damage or neuropathy, which can cause pain, numbness, or tingling sensations\r\nInfections, such as athlete\'s foot, toenail fungus, or cellulitis', 'The treatment for foot pain will depend on the underlying cause. Some general treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Resting and avoiding activities that exacerbate the pain\r\n•	Applying ice to the affected area to reduce inflammation and swelling\r\n•	Elevating the foot to reduce swelling\r\n•	Taking over-the-counter pain relievers, such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen\r\n•	Wearing comfortable and supportive shoes\r\n•	Using orthotic inserts or arch supports to alleviate pressure on the feet\r\n•	Stretching exercises to improve flexibility and prevent future injuries\r\n•	Physical therapy to improve strength and mobility\r\n•	In some cases, surgery may be necessary, such as for severe injuries or medical conditions.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if the foot pain is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, swelling, or redness. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further complications and improve outcomes.'),
(72, 'Gagging ', 'Gagging is a reflexive action that occurs when the body tries to expel something that is irritating or obstructing the throat or airway. It is a normal physiological response and can occur in a variety of situations, such as when swallowing large chunks of food, when vomiting, or when having dental procedures.\r\n\r\nHowever, gagging can also be a symptom of an underlying medical condition or an adverse reaction to certain medications. Some common causes of gagging include:', '•	Acid reflux or GERD (gastroesophageal reflux disease)\r\n•	Infections, such as strep throat or tonsillitis\r\n•	Allergies or sinusitis\r\n•	Dental problems, such as cavities or gum disease\r\n•	Anxiety or stress\r\n•	Side effects of certain medications, such as antidepressants or chemotherapy drugs\r\n•	Motion sickness or vertigo\r\n•	Neurological disorders, such as Parkinson\'s disease or multiple sclerosis', 'Treatment for gagging will depend on the underlying cause. Some general treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding triggers, such as certain foods, odors, or stressful situations\r\n•	Practicing relaxation techniques, such as deep breathing or meditation\r\n•	Using over-the-counter or prescription medications to alleviate symptoms, such as antacids for acid reflux or allergy medications for sinusitis\r\n•	Addressing dental problems with good oral hygiene or dental procedures\r\n•	In severe cases or those related to underlying medical conditions, referral to a specialist or additional testing may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider if the gagging is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms, such as difficulty breathing, chest pain, or fever. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further complications and improve outcomes.'),
(73, 'Gastritis ', 'Gastritis is a medical condition characterized by inflammation of the lining of the stomach. It can be acute or chronic and can result from a variety of causes.', '•	Bacterial or viral infections\r\n•	Long-term use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)\r\n•	Excessive alcohol consumption\r\n•	Stress\r\n•	Autoimmune disorders', 'There are several types of gastritis, including acute gastritis, chronic gastritis, erosive gastritis, and atrophic gastritis. Treatment for gastritis will depend on the underlying cause and type. Some general treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding triggers, such as alcohol, caffeine, spicy or acidic foods, or NSAIDs\r\n•	Eating a healthy diet rich in fiber and low in fat and processed foods\r\n•	Taking over-the-counter antacids or acid-blocking medications to relieve symptoms\r\n•	Antibiotic therapy to treat bacterial infections, such as Helicobacter pylori (H. pylori)\r\n•	Treating underlying medical conditions, such as autoimmune disorders\r\n•	Lifestyle changes, such as reducing stress and getting adequate sleep\r\n•	In severe cases or those related to underlying medical conditions, referral to a specialist or additional testing may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider if the symptoms of gastritis are severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, vomiting blood, or difficulty breathing. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further complications and improve outcomes.'),
(74, 'Groin pain', 'Groin pain refers to discomfort or pain in the area where the abdomen meets the upper thigh. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including muscle strains, hernias, and infections. Groin pain can also be a symptom of underlying medical conditions, such as arthritis or kidney stones.', '•	Muscle strains or injuries\r\n•	Inguinal hernias, which occur when a part of the intestine or other abdominal tissue protrudes through a weak point in the abdominal wall\r\n•	Femoral hernias, which occur when a part of the intestine or other abdominal tissue protrudes through a weak point in the femoral canal, located in the upper thigh\r\n•	Hip or pelvic fractures\r\n•	Infections, such as cellulitis or sexually transmitted infections (STIs)\r\n•	Kidney stones or urinary tract infections\r\n•	Arthritis or inflammation of the hip joint', 'Treatment for groin pain will depend on the underlying cause. Some general treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Rest and ice to relieve muscle strains or injuries\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain relievers or anti-inflammatory medications\r\n•	Physical therapy or stretching exercises to improve flexibility and strength\r\n•	Surgery to repair hernias or fractures, if necessary\r\n•	Antibiotics or other medications to treat infections\r\n•	Lifestyle changes, such as weight loss or avoiding certain activities that exacerbate symptoms\r\n•	In severe cases or those related to underlying medical conditions, referral to a specialist or additional testing may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider if the groin pain is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, vomiting, or difficulty walking. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further complications and improve outcomes.'),
(75, 'Gum sore', 'Gum sores, also known as canker sores or aphthous ulcers, are small, painful ulcers that develop on the gums, tongue, lips, or other areas inside the mouth. These sores can be caused by a variety of factors, including injury, stress, and certain medical conditions.', '•	Injury from accidental bites, sharp foods, or dental procedures\r\n•	Stress or anxiety\r\n•	Hormonal changes, particularly during menstruation\r\n•	Nutritional deficiencies, such as iron, vitamin B12, or folate\r\n•	Allergic reactions to certain foods or oral care products\r\n•	Inflammatory bowel disease or other autoimmune disorders\r\n•	Viral infections, such as herpes simplex virus or hand, foot, and mouth disease', 'Treatment for gum sores will depend on the underlying cause. Some general treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain relievers or topical analgesics to relieve pain and discomfort\r\n•	Oral rinses or gels containing antimicrobial or anti-inflammatory agents to reduce inflammation and promote healing\r\n•	Avoiding spicy or acidic foods that may irritate the sores\r\n•	Maintaining good oral hygiene practices, such as brushing and flossing regularly\r\n•	Applying a paste of baking soda and water to the sore to promote healing\r\n•	In severe or recurrent cases, prescription medications or referral to a specialist may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider if the gum sore is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever or difficulty eating or drinking. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further complications and improve outcomes.'),
(76, 'Hair loss', 'Hair loss, also known as alopecia, is a common condition that can affect men and women of all ages. It can occur for a variety of reasons, including genetics, medical conditions, medications, and hormonal changes.', '•	Androgenetic alopecia, which is a hereditary condition that causes hair follicles to shrink and eventually stop producing hair\r\n•	Telogen effluvium, which is a temporary condition that occurs due to physical or emotional stress, hormonal changes, or certain medications\r\n•	Alopecia areata, which is an autoimmune condition that causes the immune system to attack hair follicles\r\n•	Traction alopecia, which occurs due to tight hairstyles or braids that pull on the hair\r\n•	Nutritional deficiencies, such as iron or vitamin D deficiency\r\n•	Medical conditions, such as thyroid disorders or scalp infections\r\n•	Medications, such as chemotherapy drugs or blood thinners', 'Treatment for hair loss will depend on the underlying cause. Some general treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter minoxidil, which is a topical medication that can help stimulate hair growth\r\n•	Prescription medications, such as finasteride or dutasteride, which can help block the hormone that causes hair loss in men\r\n•	Hair transplant surgery, which involves transplanting hair follicles from one area of the scalp to another\r\n•	Low-level laser therapy, which uses light energy to stimulate hair growth\r\n•	Lifestyle changes, such as stress reduction or dietary changes, to improve overall health and wellbeing\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider or dermatologist if experiencing significant hair loss or other concerning symptoms. They can help determine the underlying cause and recommend appropriate treatment options to address the issue. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further hair loss and improve outcomes.'),
(77, 'Hallucinations ', 'Hallucinations are sensory experiences that are not based on reality. They can occur in any of the five senses (sight, hearing, taste, smell, and touch) and can be either simple or complex. Simple hallucinations are sensory experiences that are not based on reality, such as seeing flashes of light or hearing a single voice. Complex hallucinations, on the other hand, involve more elaborate sensory experiences, such as hearing multiple voices or seeing detailed images.', '•	Psychiatric disorders, such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, or major depression with psychotic features\r\n•	Substance use, including drugs such as LSD, cocaine, or methamphetamine, or alcohol withdrawal\r\n•	Neurological disorders, such as dementia, Parkinson\'s disease, or epilepsy\r\n•	Sleep disorders, such as narcolepsy or sleep deprivation\r\n•	Medical conditions, such as brain tumors or infections, high fever, or sensory deprivation', 'Treatment for hallucinations will depend on the underlying cause. For psychiatric disorders, antipsychotic medications and psychotherapy may be recommended. Substance use may require detoxification and rehabilitation, while neurological or medical conditions may require medical treatment or surgery.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if experiencing hallucinations, as they can be a symptom of a serious underlying condition. A healthcare provider or mental health professional can help diagnose the cause and recommend appropriate treatment options. Early diagnosis and treatment can help manage symptoms and improve outcomes.'),
(78, 'Hand pain', 'Hand pain can be caused by a variety of factors and can range from mild discomfort to severe pain that affects daily activities. Hand pain can be localized to a specific area of the hand or can be felt throughout the entire hand. It can also be accompanied by other symptoms, such as swelling, redness, or stiffness.', '•	Injuries, such as sprains, strains, fractures, or dislocations\r\n•	Overuse, such as from repetitive activities like typing or playing a musical instrument\r\n•	Arthritis, including osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis\r\n•	Carpal tunnel syndrome, a condition that occurs when the median nerve is compressed as it travels through the wrist\r\n•	Trigger finger, a condition that causes a finger to become stuck in a bent position\r\n•	Tendinitis, inflammation of a tendon\r\n•	Nerve damage, such as from a pinched nerve or peripheral neuropathy\r\n•	Infections, such as cellulitis or septic arthritis', 'The treatment for hand pain will depend on the underlying cause. For minor injuries, rest and ice may be sufficient. More serious injuries may require immobilization or surgery. In cases of arthritis or tendinitis, physical therapy, medication, or injections may be recommended. Carpal tunnel syndrome and trigger finger may require surgery. Nerve damage may be treated with medication or surgery. Infections will require appropriate antibiotics or other medical treatments.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention for persistent or severe hand pain, as it can impact daily activities and quality of life. A healthcare provider or specialist can help diagnose the cause of hand pain and recommend appropriate treatment options.'),
(79, 'Headaches', 'Headaches are a common condition that most people experience at some point in their lives. They can be described as a dull ache or throbbing pain in the head, and can vary in intensity and location. Headaches can be classified into two types: primary headaches and secondary headaches.', 'Primary headaches are caused by problems with the structures in the head that are pain-sensitive, such as blood vessels, muscles, and nerves. These include:\r\n\r\n•	Tension headaches: the most common type of headache that is often caused by stress or tension in the muscles of the head and neck\r\n•	Migraine headaches: severe, recurrent headaches that are often accompanied by other symptoms, such as nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound\r\n•	Cluster headaches: rare, but extremely painful headaches that occur in clusters or cycles, usually on one side of the head\r\n\r\nSecondary headaches, on the other hand, are caused by an underlying medical condition, such as:\r\n\r\n•	Sinusitis or allergies\r\n•	Dental problems or jaw disorders\r\n•	Head injury or concussion\r\n•	Infection, such as meningitis or encephalitis\r\n•	High blood pressure or other cardiovascular problems\r\n•	Brain tumors or other neurological conditions', 'Treatment for headaches will depend on the type and underlying cause of the headache. For primary headaches, over-the-counter pain medications, such as aspirin or ibuprofen, can be effective in relieving pain. Lifestyle changes, such as getting enough sleep, managing stress, and avoiding triggers, can also help prevent headaches from occurring. For more severe or frequent headaches, prescription medications or preventative therapies may be recommended.\r\n\r\nFor secondary headaches, treatment will depend on the underlying medical condition. For example, sinusitis may be treated with antibiotics, while jaw disorders may be treated with dental or orthodontic procedures. It is important to seek medical attention for persistent or severe headaches, as they can be a symptom of a more serious underlying condition.\r\n\r\nOverall, headaches can be managed with appropriate treatment and lifestyle changes, allowing individuals to better manage their symptoms and improve their quality of life.'),
(80, 'Heartburn', 'Heartburn, also known as acid reflux, is a common condition that causes a burning sensation in the chest and throat. It occurs when stomach acid flows back up into the esophagus, the tube that connects the throat to the stomach. This can cause irritation and inflammation of the lining of the esophagus, resulting in a variety of symptoms.', 'The main cause of heartburn is a weakened lower esophageal sphincter (LES), which is the muscle that controls the opening and closing of the esophagus. When the LES is weakened, stomach acid can flow back up into the esophagus, causing the symptoms of heartburn.\r\n\r\nOther factors that can contribute to heartburn include:\r\n\r\n•	Eating large meals or lying down immediately after eating\r\n•	Being overweight or obese\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Smoking or exposure to secondhand smoke\r\n•	Certain medications, such as aspirin, ibuprofen, and some blood pressure medications\r\n•	Eating spicy, fatty, or acidic foods\r\n•	Stress and anxiety', 'The treatment of heartburn depends on the severity and frequency of the symptoms. Mild or occasional heartburn can often be managed with lifestyle changes, such as:\r\n\r\n•	Eating smaller, more frequent meals\r\n•	Avoiding trigger foods and drinks\r\n•	Avoiding lying down immediately after eating\r\n•	Maintaining a healthy weight\r\n•	Quitting smoking\r\n•	Reducing stress and anxiety\r\n\r\nOver-the-counter antacids and acid reducers, such as ranitidine or famotidine, can also be effective in relieving symptoms of heartburn. If these measures are not effective, prescription medications, such as proton pump inhibitors or H2 blockers, may be recommended.\r\n\r\nIn addition to medical treatments, there are also some natural remedies that can help manage symptoms of heartburn, such as:\r\n\r\n•	Drinking ginger tea\r\n•	Chewing gum\r\n•	Drinking apple cider vinegar\r\n•	Eating bananas or melons\r\n•	Taking aloe vera supplements\r\n•	It is important to seek medical attention if heartburn is severe or persistent, or if it interferes with daily activities. Long-term untreated heartburn can lead to complications such as esophagitis, ulcers, and Barrett\'s esophagus, which is a precancerous condition.'),
(81, 'Heel pain', 'Heel pain is a common condition that can affect individuals of all ages, causing discomfort and limiting mobility. It typically presents as pain in the heel or bottom of the foot, especially when weight-bearing or walking.', 'The most common cause of heel pain is plantar fasciitis, which is an inflammation of the plantar fascia. The plantar fascia is a thick band of tissue that connects the heel bone to the toes and supports the arch of the foot. When it becomes inflamed or irritated, it can cause pain and tenderness in the heel. Other causes of heel pain include:\r\n\r\n•	Achilles tendinitis: Inflammation of the Achilles tendon, which runs from the calf muscle to the heel bone.\r\n\r\n•	Heel spurs: Bony growths that develop on the underside of the heel bone.\r\n\r\n•	Stress fractures: Tiny cracks in the bones of the foot, usually caused by repetitive impact.\r\n\r\n•	Bursitis: Inflammation of the fluid-filled sacs (bursae) that cushion the joints.\r\n\r\n•	Tarsal tunnel syndrome: Compression of the nerves that run through the ankle into the foot.\r\n\r\n•	Arthritis: Inflammation of the joints in the foot.', 'Treatment for heel pain depends on the underlying cause. For mild cases of plantar fasciitis, rest, ice, stretching, and wearing supportive footwear may be enough to reduce pain and inflammation. More severe cases may require physical therapy, corticosteroid injections, or even surgery. Treatment for other causes of heel pain may include:\r\n\r\n•	Achilles tendinitis: Rest, ice, physical therapy, and sometimes surgery.\r\n\r\n•	Heel spurs: Orthotic devices, physical therapy, and sometimes surgery.\r\n\r\n•	Stress fractures: Rest, ice, and sometimes a cast or walking boot.\r\n\r\n•	Bursitis: Rest, ice, and sometimes corticosteroid injections.\r\n\r\n•	Tarsal tunnel syndrome: Rest, physical therapy, and sometimes surgery.\r\n\r\n•	Arthritis: Anti-inflammatory medications, physical therapy, and sometimes surgery.'),
(82, 'High blood pressure', 'High blood pressure, also known as hypertension, is a common medical condition where the force of blood against the walls of the arteries is consistently too high. Over time, this can cause damage to the blood vessels and increase the risk of serious health problems, such as heart attack, stroke, and kidney disease.', '•	Genetics and family history\r\n•	Aging\r\n•	Poor diet and lack of exercise\r\n•	Obesity or being overweight\r\n•	Smoking\r\n•	Stress and anxiety\r\n•	Certain medications or underlying medical conditions\r\n\r\nMany people with high blood pressure do not experience any symptoms, which is why it is often called the \"silent killer.\" However, some people with high blood pressure may experience headaches, shortness of breath, or nosebleeds.', 'The treatment for high blood pressure involves lifestyle changes and medications. Lifestyle changes may include:\r\n\r\n•	Eating a healthy, low-sodium diet\r\n•	Engaging in regular physical activity\r\n•	Maintaining a healthy weight\r\n•	Limiting alcohol intake\r\n•	Managing stress\r\n•	Quitting smoking\r\n\r\nIn addition to lifestyle changes, medications may also be prescribed to lower blood pressure. These medications work in different ways to relax blood vessels, reduce fluid buildup, or decrease the heart\'s workload.\r\n\r\nIt is important to regularly monitor blood pressure, as high blood pressure can cause damage to the body over time. People with high blood pressure should work closely with their healthcare provider to manage their condition and prevent complications.'),
(83, 'Hip pain', 'Hip pain is a common symptom that can occur due to a variety of reasons. It can be a result of an injury, overuse, or an underlying medical condition. The hip joint is the largest weight-bearing joint in the human body, and it connects the thigh bone (femur) to the pelvis. It is responsible for supporting the body\'s weight and facilitating movement.', '•	Arthritis\r\n•	Hip fractures\r\n•	Bursitis\r\n•	Tendinitis\r\n•	Muscle strain\r\n•	Hip labral tear\r\n•	Sciatica\r\n•	Hernia\r\n•	Osteonecrosis', 'The treatment for hip pain depends on the underlying cause. Some common treatment options include:\r\n\r\n•	Rest and avoiding activities that exacerbate the pain\r\n•	Ice or heat therapy\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain medications such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen\r\n•	Physical therapy to improve strength and flexibility\r\n•	Injections such as corticosteroids to reduce inflammation\r\n•	Surgery for severe cases or underlying conditions such as hip fractures or arthritis.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if the hip pain is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms. Early intervention and proper treatment can help prevent further damage and improve the chances of a successful recovery.'),
(84, 'Hyperventilation', 'Hyperventilation is a condition where a person breathes too rapidly or deeply, leading to an increased amount of oxygen and a decreased level of carbon dioxide in the blood. This can cause a variety of symptoms, including lightheadedness, dizziness, shortness of breath, and tingling in the hands and feet.', '•	Anxiety or panic attacks\r\n•	Stress or emotional trauma\r\n•	Physical exertion or exercise\r\n•	High altitude\r\n•	Medical conditions such as asthma, pneumonia, or heart disease\r\n•	Side effects of certain medications.', 'The treatment for hyperventilation depends on the underlying cause. Some common treatment options include:\r\n\r\n•	Breathing exercises to slow down and regulate breathing\r\n•	Relaxation techniques such as deep breathing or meditation\r\n•	Anxiety or stress management techniques\r\n•	Medications such as anti-anxiety medications or bronchodilators for underlying medical conditions.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if hyperventilation is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms. Early intervention and proper treatment can help prevent further complications and improve the chances of a successful recovery.'),
(85, 'Increased appetite', 'Increased appetite, also known as polyphagia, is a condition where a person feels an excessive hunger or a persistent desire to eat. This can lead to consuming larger amounts of food than usual, resulting in weight gain and other health complications.', '•	Diabetes: High blood sugar levels can cause increased hunger.\r\n•	Hormonal imbalances: Conditions like hyperthyroidism can cause an increased appetite.\r\n•	Stress or emotional factors: Anxiety or depression can increase appetite.\r\n•	Medications: Certain medications like corticosteroids can increase appetite.\r\n•	Chronic diseases: Certain chronic diseases like cancer or liver disease can cause increased hunger.', 'The treatment for increased appetite involves identifying and treating the underlying cause. Depending on the cause, the treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Dietary changes: A well-balanced diet can help regulate appetite.\r\n•	Exercise: Regular physical activity can help regulate hunger hormones.\r\n•	Medications: In some cases, medications may be prescribed to control appetite.\r\n•	Psychological counseling: If stress or emotional factors are the underlying cause, counseling or therapy may be recommended.\r\n•	Treatment of underlying medical conditions: Treatment of underlying medical conditions like diabetes or hyperthyroidism can help control appetite.\r\n\r\nIf left untreated, increased appetite can lead to various health complications like obesity, diabetes, high blood pressure, and heart disease. Therefore, it is essential to seek medical attention if experiencing persistent hunger or uncontrolled appetite.'),
(86, 'Increased thirst', 'Increased thirst, also known as polydipsia, is a condition characterized by an abnormal or excessive need to drink fluids. This can be a sign of an underlying medical condition, and it is important to seek medical attention if the increased thirst persists.', '•	Diabetes: High blood sugar levels can cause excessive thirst.\r\n•	Dehydration: Inadequate fluid intake or excessive sweating can lead to increased thirst.\r\n•	Certain medications: Certain medications like diuretics or antihistamines can cause increased thirst.\r\n•	Hormonal imbalances: Conditions like hyperthyroidism can cause increased thirst.', 'The treatment for increased thirst involves identifying and treating the underlying cause. Depending on the cause, the treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Fluid replacement: Adequate fluid intake can help alleviate symptoms of dehydration.\r\n•	Medications: In some cases, medications may be prescribed to manage underlying medical conditions.\r\n•	Dietary changes: A well-balanced diet can help regulate thirst.\r\nLifestyle changes: Lifestyle changes like reducing alcohol or caffeine intake can help alleviate symptoms.\r\n\r\nIf left untreated, increased thirst can lead to various health complications like dehydration, kidney damage, and electrolyte imbalances. Therefore, it is essential to seek medical attention if experiencing persistent thirst or excessive fluid intake.'),
(87, 'Insomnia ', 'Insomnia is a sleep disorder that affects a significant number of people worldwide. It is characterized by difficulty falling asleep or staying asleep, leading to poor quality sleep and feeling tired and unrefreshed during the day. Insomnia can be classified as acute or chronic, with acute insomnia lasting for a few days to weeks and chronic insomnia lasting for several months or even years.', '•	Stress and anxiety\r\n•	Poor sleep habits\r\n•	Medical conditions like chronic pain, depression, and sleep apnea\r\n•	Certain medications like antidepressants or stimulants\r\n•	Substance abuse, including alcohol and caffeine', 'The treatment for insomnia involves identifying and treating the underlying cause. Depending on the cause, the treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Sleep hygiene: Practicing good sleep habits like maintaining a regular sleep schedule and avoiding stimulants before bedtime.\r\n•	Cognitive-behavioral therapy: A type of therapy that helps identify and change negative thoughts and behaviors that affect sleep.\r\n•	Medications: In some cases, medications may be prescribed to help with insomnia.\r\n•	Treatment of underlying medical conditions: Treating medical conditions like sleep apnea, depression, or chronic pain can help alleviate insomnia symptoms.\r\n\r\nIf left untreated, chronic insomnia can have serious consequences like impaired daytime functioning, increased risk of accidents, and a higher risk of developing mental health disorders like depression or anxiety. Therefore, it is essential to seek medical attention if experiencing persistent insomnia symptoms.'),
(88, 'Irregular heartbeat', 'An irregular heartbeat, also known as arrhythmia, is a condition in which the heart beats too fast, too slow, or irregularly. It is a relatively common condition that can affect people of all ages. In most cases, arrhythmias are not life-threatening, but some types of arrhythmias can be serious and require medical attention.', '•	Heart disease, such as coronary artery disease or heart valve disorders\r\n•	High blood pressure\r\n•	Electrolyte imbalances, such as low potassium or magnesium levels\r\n•	Overactive or underactive thyroid gland\r\n•	Excessive alcohol or caffeine consumption\r\n•	Stress or anxiety\r\n•	Certain medications, such as those used to treat high blood pressure or heart disease\r\n•	Congenital heart defects\r\n•	Smoking', 'Treatment for an irregular heartbeat depends on the type and severity of the arrhythmia. In some cases, no treatment is necessary, and the arrhythmia may resolve on its own. However, other cases may require medical intervention, such as:\r\n\r\n•	Medications to regulate heart rhythm or control the underlying cause of the arrhythmia\r\n•	Electrical cardioversion, which uses an electrical shock to restore normal heart rhythm\r\n•	Catheter ablation, which involves using radiofrequency energy to destroy small areas of heart tissue that are causing the arrhythmia\r\n•	Implantable devices, such as a pacemaker or implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (ICD), which can help regulate heart rhythm or deliver a shock if needed\r\n\r\nIf you experience symptoms of an irregular heartbeat, it is essential to seek medical attention. In some cases, an irregular heartbeat can be a sign of a more serious underlying condition that requires treatment.'),
(89, 'Irregular periods', 'Irregular periods, also known as irregular menstrual cycles, is a common condition that affects many women at some point in their lives. A menstrual cycle is considered irregular if the length of time between periods varies by more than a few days from month to month. In some cases, women may experience missed periods or periods that last longer than usual.', '•	Hormonal imbalances, such as polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) or thyroid disorders\r\n•	Stress or emotional turmoil\r\n•	Rapid weight gain or loss\r\n•	Extreme exercise or athletic training\r\n•	Certain medications, such as those used to treat epilepsy or depression\r\n•	Breastfeeding or pregnancy\r\n•	Perimenopause or menopause', 'Treatment for irregular periods depends on the underlying cause of the condition. In some cases, no treatment is necessary, and the menstrual cycle may regulate on its own. However, other cases may require medical intervention, such as:\r\n\r\n•	Hormonal therapy, such as birth control pills or hormone replacement therapy\r\n•	Medications to regulate ovulation, such as Clomid or letrozole\r\n•	Surgery to remove uterine fibroids or other growths that may be causing the irregular periods\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing irregular periods, it is essential to talk to your healthcare provider. They can help determine the underlying cause of the condition and develop a treatment plan that is right for you.'),
(90, 'Itching or burning', 'Itching or burning sensations can occur in various parts of the body and may be a sign of an underlying condition or simply a temporary discomfort. These sensations can be caused by a variety of factors, including skin irritants, allergic reactions, infections, and medical conditions.', '•	Skin irritants such as harsh soaps, detergents, or fabrics\r\n•	Allergic reactions to foods, medications, or environmental triggers like pollen or pet dander\r\n•	Skin conditions such as eczema, psoriasis, or dermatitis\r\n•	Infections such as bacterial or fungal infections of the skin, vagina, or urinary tract\r\n•	Nerve damage or neurological conditions like shingles or diabetic neuropathy\r\n•	Hormonal changes such as menopause or thyroid dysfunction\r\n•	Medical conditions such as kidney disease, liver disease, or cancer', 'The treatment of itching or burning sensations depends on the underlying cause of the condition. Some common treatments may include:\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding skin irritants or allergens\r\n•	Applying over-the-counter creams or lotions to soothe the skin\r\n•	Prescription medications to treat infections or underlying medical conditions\r\n•	Antihistamines or other allergy medications to relieve itching caused by allergies\r\n•	Cool compresses or baths to reduce inflammation and soothe the skin\r\n•	Lifestyle changes such as stress reduction, avoiding hot showers or baths, and maintaining a healthy diet and exercise routine\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing persistent or severe itching or burning sensations, it is important to talk to your healthcare provider. They can help determine the underlying cause of your symptoms and develop a treatment plan that is right for you.'),
(91, 'Jaw clicking', 'Jaw clicking is a common symptom that may be accompanied by pain, stiffness, or difficulty opening the mouth. It occurs when the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) clicks or pops while opening or closing the mouth.', '•	Injury to the jaw or temporomandibular joint\r\n•	Arthritis or degenerative joint disease\r\n•	Bruxism, which is the clenching or grinding of teeth\r\n•	Misalignment of the teeth or jaw\r\n•	Stress or anxiety, which can cause tension in the jaw muscles\r\n•	Overuse or fatigue of the jaw muscles', 'In most cases, jaw clicking is not a serious medical condition and can be managed with self-care and lifestyle changes. Some tips to manage jaw clicking include:\r\n\r\n•	Eating soft foods and avoiding hard or chewy foods\r\n•	Applying warm compresses to the jaw to reduce pain and stiffness\r\n•	Performing gentle jaw exercises to improve mobility and strengthen the muscles\r\n•	Avoiding activities that require prolonged or excessive use of the jaw, such as singing or playing a musical instrument\r\n•	Managing stress and anxiety through relaxation techniques or counseling\r\n\r\nIf the jaw clicking is accompanied by persistent pain or difficulty opening the mouth, it is important to see a healthcare provider for evaluation. They may recommend further testing or refer you to a specialist, such as an oral surgeon or physical therapist, for further evaluation and treatment. In some cases, medications, injections, or surgery may be recommended to manage more severe cases of jaw clicking.'),
(92, 'Jaw locking', 'Jaw locking occurs when the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) becomes dislocated, preventing normal movement of the jaw. This can result in difficulty opening or closing the mouth, and may be accompanied by pain, discomfort, or a popping or clicking sensation in the jaw.', '•	Injury or trauma to the jaw or TMJ\r\n•	Bruxism, which is the clenching or grinding of teeth\r\n•	Arthritis or degenerative joint disease\r\n•	Misalignment of the teeth or jaw\r\n•	Stress or anxiety, which can cause tension in the jaw muscles', 'In some cases, jaw locking may resolve on its own with self-care and lifestyle changes. Some tips to manage jaw locking include:\r\n\r\n•	Applying moist heat or ice to the jaw to reduce pain and inflammation\r\n•	Eating soft foods and avoiding hard or chewy foods\r\n•	Performing gentle jaw exercises to improve mobility and strengthen the muscles\r\n•	Using over-the-counter pain medications, such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen, to manage pain and discomfort\r\n•	Avoiding activities that require prolonged or excessive use of the jaw, such as singing or playing a musical instrument\r\n\r\nIf self-care measures do not improve the symptoms, a healthcare provider may recommend further testing or refer you to a specialist, such as an oral surgeon or physical therapist, for further evaluation and treatment. In some cases, medications, injections, or surgery may be recommended to manage more severe cases of jaw locking.'),
(93, 'Jaw pain', 'Jaw pain can be caused by a variety of factors, ranging from minor issues such as toothaches to more serious conditions like temporomandibular joint disorder (TMJ). Jaw pain may also be accompanied by other symptoms, such as difficulty opening or closing the mouth, clicking or popping sounds when moving the jaw, and headaches.', '•	Dental problems, such as tooth decay or gum disease\r\n•	Bruxism, which is the clenching or grinding of teeth\r\n•	Temporomandibular joint disorder (TMJ), which is a condition that affects the joint connecting the jawbone to the skull\r\n•	Trauma or injury to the jaw or face\r\n•	Sinus infections or other sinus-related problems\r\n•	Arthritis or other degenerative joint conditions\r\n•	Neuralgia, which is a nerve-related pain condition\r\n•	Oral cancer, although this is rare', 'Treatment for jaw pain will depend on the underlying cause. Some common treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain medications such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen\r\n•	Warm or cold compresses to the affected area\r\n•	Mouthguards or splints to help prevent grinding or clenching of teeth\r\n•	Prescription medications or muscle relaxants\r\n•	Physical therapy to improve jaw function and reduce pain\r\n•	Surgery in more severe cases.\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider if you are experiencing persistent or severe jaw pain, as they can help identify the underlying cause and recommend appropriate treatment.'),
(94, 'Joint ache', 'Joint ache is a common symptom that can be caused by a variety of factors. It can affect any joint in the body, including the knees, hips, shoulders, and hands. Joint ache may be accompanied by other symptoms, such as stiffness, swelling, and redness.', '•	Arthritis, which is inflammation of the joints\r\n•	Osteoarthritis, which is a degenerative joint disease that commonly affects older adults\r\n•	Rheumatoid arthritis, which is an autoimmune disease that affects the joints\r\n•	Gout, which is a type of arthritis caused by the buildup of uric acid crystals in the joints\r\n•	Bursitis, which is inflammation of the fluid-filled sacs that cushion the joints\r\n•	Tendinitis, which is inflammation of the tendons that attach muscles to bones\r\n•	Strains or sprains, which are injuries to the muscles, ligaments, or tendons around the joints\r\n•	Lyme disease, which is a bacterial infection transmitted by tick bites', 'Treatment for joint ache will depend on the underlying cause. Some common treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain medications such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen\r\n•	Topical creams or ointments to reduce inflammation and pain\r\n•	Resting the affected joint and avoiding activities that exacerbate the pain\r\n•	Applying heat or cold to the affected joint\r\n•	Physical therapy to strengthen the muscles around the joint and improve flexibility\r\n•	Prescription medications such as corticosteroids or disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs)\r\n•	Surgery in more severe cases.\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider if you are experiencing persistent or severe joint pain, as they can help identify the underlying cause and recommend appropriate treatment.'),
(95, 'Joint cracking', 'Joint cracking, also known as joint popping, is a common phenomenon where you hear a cracking or popping sound in your joints when you move them. While joint cracking can occur in any joint in the body, it is most commonly experienced in the fingers, neck, shoulders, knees, and back.\r\n\r\nThe cracking sound you hear is caused by the release of gas bubbles that have built up in the joint fluid. When you move your joint, the pressure in the joint decreases, causing the gas bubbles to rapidly collapse, creating the cracking sound.', '•	Gas bubbles: As mentioned earlier, the most common cause of joint cracking is the release of gas bubbles from the joint fluid.\r\n\r\n•	Tendons snapping: When you move a joint, the tendons that attach to it can sometimes snap against bone or other tendons, causing a popping sound.\r\n\r\n•	Arthritis: Joint cracking can be a symptom of arthritis, a condition that causes inflammation in the joints, leading to pain, stiffness, and swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Ligament injuries: If you have a ligament injury, such as a sprain, you may experience joint cracking as a result of the joint becoming unstable.\r\n\r\n•	Cartilage damage: Joint cracking can also be a symptom of cartilage damage, which can occur as a result of injury, overuse, or age-related wear and tear.', 'If you experience joint cracking without any pain or other symptoms, there is usually no need for treatment. However, if the cracking is accompanied by pain, swelling, stiffness, or reduced range of motion, you should see a doctor.\r\n\r\nTreatment for joint cracking will depend on the underlying cause. If it is caused by arthritis or other medical conditions, your doctor may prescribe medication or physical therapy to help manage your symptoms. If it is caused by an injury, such as a ligament sprain, you may need to rest the joint and use ice or heat to reduce inflammation. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to repair damaged cartilage or ligaments.'),
(96, 'Joint locking', 'Joint locking refers to the condition where a joint gets stuck or becomes difficult to move. This can be a temporary or chronic issue, and it can occur in any joint in the body. Joint locking can cause discomfort and pain, and it can interfere with daily activities.', '•	Injury: An injury, such as a sprain or strain, can cause joint locking.\r\n\r\n•	Arthritis: Arthritis can cause joint locking due to the inflammation and degeneration of cartilage in the joint.\r\n\r\n•	Dislocation: When a joint becomes dislocated, it can cause the joint to lock in place.\r\n\r\n•	Tendinitis: Inflammation of the tendons around a joint can cause joint locking.\r\n\r\n•	Osteochondritis dissecans: This condition occurs when a piece of cartilage or bone breaks loose and becomes lodged in the joint, causing locking.\r\n\r\n•	Meniscus tears: The meniscus is a piece of cartilage that acts as a cushion in the knee joint. When it tears, it can cause locking in the knee.', 'The treatment for joint locking depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, joint locking can be treated with simple remedies such as:\r\n\r\n•	Rest: Resting the joint can help reduce inflammation and alleviate symptoms.\r\n\r\n•	Heat or ice: Applying heat or ice to the joint can help reduce pain and inflammation.\r\n\r\n•	Physical therapy: Physical therapy can help strengthen the muscles around the joint and improve flexibility.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Over-the-counter pain medications such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen can help alleviate pain and reduce inflammation.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, surgery may be necessary to repair the joint and alleviate locking. Joint locking can be a chronic issue, so it\'s important to consult a doctor if symptoms persist or worsen.'),
(97, 'Knee pain', 'Knee pain is a common complaint among people of all ages. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including injury, overuse, or underlying medical conditions. The knee joint is a complex joint that is made up of bones, ligaments, tendons, and cartilage. It is responsible for bearing the weight of the body and enabling movement of the legs.', '•	Injuries to the knee joint, such as a ligament tear, meniscus tear, or fracture.\r\n•	Overuse or repetitive strain on the knee joint, which can lead to conditions such as patellofemoral pain syndrome or iliotibial band syndrome.\r\n•	Arthritis, which can cause inflammation and pain in the knee joint.\r\n•	Bursitis, which is inflammation of the bursae, small fluid-filled sacs that cushion the knee joint.\r\n•	Tendinitis, which is inflammation of the tendons that attach muscles to bones.\r\n•	Osteoporosis, a condition that causes bones to weaken and become more susceptible to fracture.\r\n•	Gout, a type of arthritis that is caused by a buildup of uric acid crystals in the joint.', 'The treatment for knee pain depends on the cause and severity of the pain. Some general treatments for knee pain include:\r\n\r\n•	Resting and avoiding activities that cause pain or discomfort.\r\n•	Applying ice or heat to the knee to reduce inflammation and relieve pain.\r\n•	Taking over-the-counter pain medications such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen.\r\n•	Doing exercises to strengthen the muscles around the knee joint, which can help provide support and reduce pain.\r\n•	Using assistive devices such as knee braces or crutches to reduce pressure on the knee joint.\r\n\r\nIn more severe cases, surgery may be necessary to repair or replace damaged parts of the knee joint.'),
(98, 'Knee swelling', 'Knee swelling refers to the accumulation of fluid within the knee joint, resulting in an enlargement of the knee. It is a common symptom of knee injuries and underlying medical conditions.', '•	Knee injuries such as sprains, strains, fractures, and ligament tears\r\n•	Knee osteoarthritis\r\n•	Rheumatoid arthritis\r\n•	Gout\r\n•	Baker\'s cysts\r\n•	Infections\r\n•	Bursitis\r\n•	Tendinitis', 'The general treatment of knee swelling includes:\r\n\r\n•	Rest and elevation of the affected knee\r\n•	Application of ice packs to the knee to reduce swelling\r\n•	Use of compression bandages or knee braces\r\n•	Administration of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) to relieve pain and inflammation\r\n•	Physical therapy to strengthen the knee muscles and improve range of motion\r\n•	Drainage of the accumulated fluid through a needle\r\n•	Surgery in severe cases\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if knee swelling is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms such as fever or chills.'),
(99, 'Leg pain', 'Leg pain refers to any discomfort or pain experienced in the leg, below the hip and above the ankle. Leg pain can range from mild to severe and can be caused by a variety of factors.', '•	Muscle strain or sprain\r\n•	Overuse or repetitive motion injuries\r\n•	Bone fractures\r\n•	Arthritis\r\n•	Peripheral artery disease\r\n•	Deep vein thrombosis\r\n•	Nerve damage\r\n•	Sciatica\r\n•	Restless legs syndrome', 'The general treatment for leg pain depends on the underlying cause, and may include:\r\n\r\n•	Rest and elevation of the affected leg\r\n•	Use of ice packs or heat therapy\r\n•	Compression stockings or bandages\r\n•	Administration of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) or pain relievers\r\n•	Physical therapy or stretching exercises\r\n•	Surgery in severe cases\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if leg pain is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms such as fever or loss of sensation. Additionally, sudden, severe leg pain or swelling should be evaluated immediately, as it could be a sign of a blood clot or other serious condition.');
INSERT INTO `symptoms` (`symptom_id`, `symptom_name`, `description`, `causes`, `treatment`) VALUES
(100, 'Leg swelling', 'Leg swelling, also known as edema, is a common condition that occurs when there is an abnormal accumulation of fluid in the legs. This can lead to a feeling of tightness, discomfort, and heaviness in the legs. While it is often a symptom of an underlying condition, it can also occur on its own.', '•	Prolonged standing or sitting: When a person stands or sits for long periods of time, blood flow can become restricted, leading to leg swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Injury: Injuries, such as sprains or fractures, can cause fluid to accumulate in the legs, leading to swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Infection: Infections can cause inflammation in the legs, leading to swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Chronic venous insufficiency: This is a condition in which the veins in the legs do not work properly, leading to swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Deep vein thrombosis: This is a blood clot that forms in a deep vein in the leg, causing swelling and pain.\r\n\r\n•	Heart failure: When the heart is not able to pump blood efficiently, fluid can accumulate in the legs.\r\n\r\n•	Kidney disease: Kidney disease can cause fluid to accumulate in the legs due to a build-up of waste in the body.', 'Treatment for leg swelling depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, the swelling may go away on its own, especially if it is caused by prolonged standing or sitting. However, if the swelling is caused by an underlying condition, treatment may include:\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Medications, such as diuretics, can help to reduce the amount of fluid in the body, which can reduce leg swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Compression stockings: Compression stockings can help to improve blood flow in the legs and reduce swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Lifestyle changes: Making lifestyle changes, such as losing weight, exercising regularly, and reducing salt intake, can help to reduce leg swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Surgery: In some cases, surgery may be necessary to treat the underlying condition that is causing leg swelling.\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing leg swelling, it is important to speak with your healthcare provider to determine the underlying cause and develop an appropriate treatment plan.'),
(101, 'Lightheadedness ', 'Lightheadedness is a common symptom that describes the feeling of dizziness or faintness. It can be a sensation of dizziness, unsteadiness, or a feeling of being about to faint. It is often accompanied by other symptoms such as nausea, weakness, confusion, blurred vision, and ringing in the ears. Lightheadedness is usually temporary and can be relieved by lying down or sitting.', '•	Dehydration: Lack of fluids in the body can cause a drop in blood pressure and lead to lightheadedness.\r\n\r\n•	Low blood sugar: Low blood sugar can cause dizziness, weakness, and lightheadedness.\r\n\r\n•	Hyperventilation: Over-breathing can cause lightheadedness by reducing the amount of carbon dioxide in the blood.\r\n\r\n•	Anemia: A lack of red blood cells in the body can cause lightheadedness due to a lack of oxygen to the brain.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Some medications can cause lightheadedness as a side effect.\r\n\r\n•	Heart problems: Certain heart conditions can cause lightheadedness, including arrhythmias, heart attack, and heart failure.\r\n\r\n•	Anxiety and stress: Lightheadedness can be a symptom of anxiety or stress.', 'Treatment for lightheadedness depends on the underlying cause. In most cases, lightheadedness is a temporary symptom that goes away on its own. However, if it persists or is accompanied by other symptoms, it is important to seek medical attention. The following treatments may be recommended:\r\n\r\n•	Drinking fluids: Dehydration is a common cause of lightheadedness, so drinking fluids can help alleviate the symptoms.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: If medications are the cause of lightheadedness, the doctor may adjust the dosage or switch to a different medication.\r\n\r\n•	Managing anxiety and stress: If anxiety or stress is the cause of lightheadedness, managing these conditions with relaxation techniques or counseling can help.\r\n\r\n•	Treatment of underlying medical conditions: If an underlying medical condition is causing lightheadedness, treating the condition may alleviate the symptom.\r\n\r\n•	Lifestyle changes: Making lifestyle changes such as eating a balanced diet, exercising regularly, and avoiding alcohol and drugs can help reduce the risk of lightheadedness.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, lightheadedness is a common symptom that can be caused by a variety of factors. While it is usually temporary and goes away on its own, it is important to seek medical attention if the symptoms persist or are accompanied by other symptoms.'),
(102, 'Limping ', 'Limping is a symptom characterized by difficulty walking normally due to an abnormal gait. The limp can vary in severity from a slight limp to an inability to walk at all. It can affect one or both legs and can occur in people of all ages.', '•	Injury: Limping can be caused by an injury to the leg or foot, such as a sprain, strain, fracture, or dislocation.\r\n\r\n•	Arthritis: Various forms of arthritis, including osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis, can cause joint pain and stiffness that lead to limping.\r\n\r\n•	Infection: Infections of the bone, joint, or muscle, such as osteomyelitis or cellulitis, can cause pain and swelling that can lead to limping.\r\n\r\n•	Neurological disorders: Disorders of the nervous system, such as cerebral palsy, multiple sclerosis, or Parkinson\'s disease, can cause weakness or spasticity that can result in limping.\r\n\r\n•	Congenital disorders: Certain congenital disorders, such as hip dysplasia, clubfoot, or muscular dystrophy, can affect the development and function of the leg and lead to limping.', 'Treatment for limping depends on the underlying cause and severity of the symptoms. Mild cases of limping may not require any treatment, while more severe cases may require medical or surgical intervention. Treatment options include:\r\n\r\n•	Rest and ice: Resting the affected leg and applying ice can help reduce pain and swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Physical therapy: A physical therapist can help improve mobility, strength, and flexibility of the leg through exercises and stretches.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Over-the-counter pain relievers, such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen, may help relieve pain and reduce inflammation.\r\n\r\n•	Assistive devices: Canes, crutches, or walkers can help reduce weight bearing on the affected leg and improve mobility.\r\n\r\n•	Surgery: In cases of severe injury or structural abnormalities, surgery may be necessary to correct the underlying problem and restore normal function to the leg.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare professional if limping persists or is accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, weakness, or numbness. Early diagnosis and treatment can help prevent further complications and improve outcomes.'),
(103, 'Loss of appetite', 'Loss of appetite is a common symptom that refers to a decrease in desire for food and a reduction in the quantity of food intake. It is a nonspecific symptom that can be caused by a wide range of factors, from mild to serious medical conditions.', '•	Infections: viral infections, bacterial infections, and parasitic infections.\r\n•	Digestive system problems: such as gastritis, gastroenteritis, inflammatory bowel disease, and peptic ulcer disease.\r\n•	Mental health issues: such as depression, anxiety, and stress.\r\n•	Cancer: such as pancreatic, liver, stomach, or colon cancer.\r\n•	Medications: such as antibiotics, chemotherapy drugs, and medications used to treat depression and anxiety.\r\n•	Hormonal imbalances: such as hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism.\r\n•	Pregnancy: in the early stages of pregnancy, some women may experience a loss of appetite.\r\n•	Chronic diseases: such as kidney disease, liver disease, and heart disease.\r\n•	Aging: the sense of smell and taste decreases with age, which can lead to a loss of appetite.', 'The treatment of loss of appetite depends on the underlying cause. It is important to identify the underlying cause of the loss of appetite and treat it accordingly. Here are some general treatment options:\r\n\r\n•	Drinking fluids to avoid dehydration.\r\n•	Eating small, frequent meals instead of three large meals a day.\r\n•	Avoiding foods that are difficult to digest, such as fatty or spicy foods.\r\n•	Taking a break from solid foods and eating foods that are easy to digest, such as soup, yogurt, or smoothies.\r\n•	Seeking treatment for underlying medical conditions, such as infections, digestive problems, or mental health issues.\r\n•	Adjusting medications that may be causing loss of appetite.\r\n•	Getting regular exercise and sleep, which can improve appetite and overall health.\r\n\r\nIf you experience a persistent loss of appetite or other concerning symptoms, it is important to seek medical attention.'),
(104, 'Loss of balance', 'Loss of balance is a feeling of unsteadiness, dizziness, or a sensation of falling or spinning, which can occur suddenly or gradually. It is a common problem that affects people of all ages and can significantly impact a person\'s quality of life, especially in older adults.', '•	Inner ear problems\r\n•	Neurological conditions, such as Parkinson\'s disease, multiple sclerosis, or stroke\r\n•	Cardiovascular problems, such as low blood pressure, heart rhythm disorders, or blocked arteries\r\n•	Musculoskeletal issues, such as arthritis, injuries, or weak muscles\r\n•	Certain medications or drug interactions\r\n•	Vision problems or eye disorders\r\n•	Anxiety or panic disorders', 'The treatment for loss of balance depends on the underlying cause. Some general treatment options include:\r\n\r\n•	Inner ear problems can be treated with medications or surgery.\r\n•	Neurological conditions may require medication or physical therapy.\r\n•	Cardiovascular problems may be treated with medication or procedures, such as pacemakers or angioplasty.\r\n•	Musculoskeletal issues may require physical therapy, rehabilitation exercises, or medication.\r\n•	Adjusting or changing certain medications or drug interactions.\r\n•	Vision problems or eye disorders may require corrective lenses or surgery.\r\n•	Anxiety or panic disorders may be treated with medication or psychotherapy.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, lifestyle changes, such as regular exercise, a balanced diet, and stress management techniques, can also help improve balance and reduce the risk of falls. It is important to consult a healthcare professional if you experience persistent or sudden loss of balance or if you have any other concerning symptoms.'),
(105, 'Loss of taste', 'Loss of taste, also known as ageusia, is a condition where a person loses their ability to taste. It can affect a person\'s enjoyment of food and may lead to malnutrition or weight loss if it persists for a long time.', '•	Illness: Illnesses such as colds, flu, and sinus infections can cause a temporary loss of taste. COVID-19 is also known to cause loss of taste in some patients.\r\n\r\n•	Aging: As a person ages, their taste buds become less sensitive, which can lead to a decreased ability to taste.\r\n\r\n•	Smoking: Smoking damages the taste buds and can lead to a loss of taste.\r\n\r\n•	Certain medications: Medications such as antibiotics, antihistamines, and chemotherapy drugs can interfere with taste.\r\n\r\n•	Head injury: A head injury that damages the nerves responsible for taste can lead to a loss of taste.\r\n\r\n•	Radiation therapy: Radiation therapy to the head and neck can damage the taste buds and cause a loss of taste.', 'Treatment for loss of taste depends on the underlying cause. If it is caused by an illness or infection, the sense of taste usually returns when the illness or infection goes away. For those whose sense of taste is affected by medications, stopping or changing the medication may help. If the loss of taste is due to aging, there is no cure, but a doctor may be able to suggest ways to enhance flavor in food.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, loss of taste can be permanent, but most people regain their sense of taste over time. In the meantime, it is important to maintain a healthy diet and seek medical attention if there are any concerns about malnutrition or weight loss.'),
(106, 'Loss of voice', 'Loss of voice, or aphonia, is a condition in which an individual experiences partial or complete loss of their ability to produce vocal sounds. It can be a temporary or permanent condition and can range from mild to severe. Loss of voice can be caused by a variety of factors, including infections, vocal cord damage, nerve damage, or certain medical conditions.', '•	Viral infections such as laryngitis, bronchitis, or the common cold\r\n•	Bacterial infections such as strep throat\r\n•	Acid reflux or gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)\r\n•	Overuse or misuse of the voice, such as shouting or screaming\r\n•	Trauma to the throat or larynx, such as a blow to the neck\r\n•	Neurological conditions such as Parkinson\'s disease or multiple sclerosis\r\n•	Vocal cord nodules, cysts, or polyps\r\n•	Cancer of the larynx or throat\r\n•	Side effects of medications', 'Treatment for loss of voice depends on the underlying cause. In most cases, the condition is temporary and will resolve on its own with rest and hydration. If the cause is an infection, antibiotics or antiviral medications may be prescribed. If the cause is acid reflux or GERD, lifestyle changes such as avoiding trigger foods, losing weight, and avoiding eating before bed may help. In some cases, voice therapy or surgery may be necessary to address vocal cord damage or other structural issues.'),
(107, 'Low blood pressure', 'Low blood pressure, also known as hypotension, is a condition where the force of blood against the walls of your arteries is too low. Blood pressure is measured in millimeters of mercury (mmHg) and consists of two numbers. The top number represents systolic blood pressure, or the pressure in your arteries when your heart beats, and the bottom number represents diastolic blood pressure, or the pressure in your arteries when your heart rests between beats.\r\n\r\nLow blood pressure is defined as a reading of less than 90/60 mmHg. However, some people may have low blood pressure and experience no symptoms, while others may have symptoms such as lightheadedness or fainting.', '•	Dehydration\r\n•	Blood loss\r\n•	Severe infection (septicemia)\r\n•	Heart disease\r\n•	Endocrine disorders, such as diabetes\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Certain medications, such as those used to treat high blood pressure or heart disease\r\n•	Allergic reactions or anaphylaxis', 'Treatment for low blood pressure depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, lifestyle changes such as increasing fluid and salt intake, and avoiding triggers such as hot temperatures or alcohol, may be recommended. If medication is the cause, the medication may be adjusted or discontinued.\r\n\r\nIf low blood pressure is due to an underlying medical condition, treatment will focus on managing that condition. For example, if low blood pressure is due to dehydration, treatment may involve fluids given through an IV. If low blood pressure is due to an allergic reaction, treatment may involve administering epinephrine. In severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary.'),
(108, 'Lump or bulge', 'A lump or bulge is an abnormal growth or swelling that appears under the skin or on the surface of the body. Lumps and bumps can be caused by a variety of conditions, ranging from harmless and temporary to serious and potentially life-threatening.', '•	Lipomas (benign tumors made of fat tissue)\r\n•	Cysts (fluid-filled sacs)\r\n•	Hematomas (collections of blood)\r\n•	Abscesses (pus-filled pockets)\r\n•	Infections (e.g. staphylococcal infections)\r\n•	Inflammation (e.g. from an injury or autoimmune disorder)\r\n•	Hernias (a protrusion of an organ or tissue through a weak spot in the muscle or connective tissue)\r\n•	Lymph nodes (swollen lymph nodes due to an infection or cancer)\r\n•	Cancer (malignant tumors)\r\n•	Trauma or injury (e.g. contusions or fractures)\r\n•	Congenital defects (e.g. birthmarks)', 'The treatment for a lump or bulge depends on its cause. In most cases, small, harmless lumps and bumps do not require treatment and may go away on their own. However, if the lump is causing discomfort or is growing larger, medical attention should be sought.\r\n\r\n•	Lipomas, cysts, and small abscesses may be removed surgically.\r\n•	Hematomas may be drained.\r\n•	Antibiotics may be prescribed for infections.\r\n•	Cancerous lumps may require chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or surgery.\r\n•	Hernias may require surgery to repair the weak spot in the muscle or connective tissue.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, a lump or bulge can have many causes, some of which are harmless and others that require immediate medical attention. Any new or unusual lump or bump should be examined by a healthcare professional to determine its cause and whether further treatment is needed.'),
(109, 'Memory loss', 'Memory loss is a condition where a person experiences a partial or total inability to recall past experiences, information, or events. This can be a frustrating and distressing experience, and can interfere with a person\'s ability to perform daily tasks, maintain relationships, and live a full life.\r\n\r\nThere are several different types of memory loss, including:\r\n\r\nShort-term memory loss: This is a type of memory loss where a person has difficulty remembering recent events or information. This can make it difficult to carry out tasks that require short-term memory, such as following a conversation or remembering a phone number.\r\n\r\nLong-term memory loss: This is a type of memory loss where a person has difficulty recalling events, information or experiences from their past. This can make it difficult to remember important life events or maintain a sense of personal identity.\r\n\r\nRetrograde amnesia: This is a type of memory loss where a person has difficulty remembering events or information that occurred before a specific point in time, such as a head injury or illness.\r\n\r\nAnterograde amnesia: This is a type of memory loss where a person has difficulty forming new memories after a specific point in time, such as a head injury or illness.', '•	Aging: As we age, our brains naturally undergo changes that can impact memory.\r\n\r\n•	Medical conditions: Certain medical conditions such as Alzheimer\'s disease, Parkinson\'s disease, multiple sclerosis, and brain tumors can cause memory loss.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Certain medications, such as those used to treat anxiety, depression, and sleep disorders, can impact memory.\r\n\r\n•	Head injuries: Traumatic brain injuries, concussions, and other head injuries can cause memory loss.\r\n\r\n•	Stress and anxiety: Chronic stress and anxiety can impact memory and cognitive function.', 'The treatment for memory loss will depend on the underlying cause. In some cases, treating an underlying medical condition may help to improve memory. In other cases, medication or therapy may be necessary to manage symptoms. Additionally, making lifestyle changes such as engaging in regular exercise, eating a healthy diet, and getting enough sleep can help to support cognitive function and improve memory.'),
(110, 'Menstrual cramps', 'Menstrual cramps are a common experience for many women during their menstrual cycle. Menstrual cramps, also known as dysmenorrhea, are typically felt as a dull or throbbing pain in the lower abdomen or pelvis, and may radiate to the lower back or thighs. Cramps can be mild or severe, and can last from a few hours to several days.', 'The causes of menstrual cramps are due to contractions of the uterus, which is a muscle. The uterus contracts in order to shed its lining during menstruation. Prostaglandins, which are hormone-like substances, trigger the uterus to contract. When there are high levels of prostaglandins in the body, the contractions can be more severe and painful.', 'There are several treatment options available for menstrual cramps. Over-the-counter pain medications such as ibuprofen and naproxen can help to reduce pain and inflammation. Heat therapy, such as a heating pad or warm bath, can also help to relieve cramps. Regular exercise and a healthy diet can also help to reduce the severity of menstrual cramps.\r\n\r\nFor women who experience severe menstrual cramps, hormonal birth control may be an effective treatment option. Hormonal birth control works by regulating hormone levels, which can reduce the amount of prostaglandins in the body and therefore reduce the severity of cramps. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to treat severe menstrual cramps that do not respond to other treatments.'),
(111, 'Metallic taste in the mouth', 'A metallic taste in the mouth, also known as dysgeusia, is an unusual or unpleasant taste in the mouth that can feel like a metallic flavor. This taste can develop suddenly or over time, and can range from mild to severe. It can be a temporary or chronic condition, depending on the underlying cause.', '•	Certain medications\r\n•	Chemotherapy or radiation therapy\r\n•	Dental problems such as gum disease, tooth infections, or poor oral hygiene\r\n•	Nutrient deficiencies, such as iron or zinc\r\n•	Exposure to certain chemicals, such as lead or mercury\r\n•	Smoking or other tobacco use\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Head injury or concussion\r\n•	Neurological disorders, such as Bell\'s palsy or multiple sclerosis\r\n•	Sinus infections or allergies', 'Treatment for a metallic taste in the mouth depends on the underlying cause. If the cause is related to a medication, switching to a different medication may help. If it is related to poor oral hygiene, improving dental care may be necessary. In some cases, treating an underlying medical condition may help to alleviate the symptom.\r\n\r\nSome home remedies that may help relieve a metallic taste in the mouth include:\r\n\r\n•	Maintaining good oral hygiene, such as brushing and flossing regularly\r\n•	Drinking plenty of water to stay hydrated\r\n•	Using sugar-free gum or candies to stimulate saliva production\r\n•	Avoiding tobacco products\r\n•	Using a tongue scraper to remove bacteria from the tongue\r\n•	Avoiding foods that may trigger the metallic taste\r\n\r\nIf the metallic taste is persistent or severe, it is recommended to consult a healthcare provider to determine the underlying cause and proper treatment plan.'),
(112, 'Migraine', 'Migraine is a neurological condition that causes severe headaches and other symptoms. It affects millions of people around the world, with women being more likely to experience migraines than men. Migraine headaches are typically characterized by intense, throbbing pain on one or both sides of the head, along with other symptoms such as sensitivity to light and sound, nausea, and vomiting.\r\n\r\nMigraines can be divided into two types: migraine with aura and migraine without aura. Migraine with aura is characterized by visual disturbances, such as flashes of light or blind spots, that occur before the headache begins. Migraine without aura, on the other hand, does not have any associated visual disturbances.', 'The exact cause of migraines is not fully understood, but it is believed to be related to changes in the brain and nervous system. Migraines are often triggered by certain factors, such as stress, lack of sleep, hormonal changes, certain foods, and environmental factors.', 'Treatment for migraines typically involves a combination of medication and lifestyle changes. Over-the-counter pain relievers, such as ibuprofen and acetaminophen, can be used to treat mild to moderate migraine pain. For more severe migraines, prescription medications, such as triptans, may be necessary. Lifestyle changes, such as getting enough sleep, reducing stress, and avoiding trigger foods and environmental factors, can also help prevent migraines. In some cases, alternative therapies, such as acupuncture, biofeedback, and massage, may be beneficial for migraine sufferers.'),
(113, 'Missed or late periods', 'Missed or late periods, also known as amenorrhea, refers to the absence of menstrual periods in women of reproductive age. While a missed period can be a normal occurrence in some cases, it can also be an indication of an underlying medical condition.', '•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS)\r\n•	Thyroid disorders\r\n•	Excessive exercise\r\n•	Stress\r\n•	Eating disorders\r\n•	Certain medications\r\n•	Breastfeeding\r\n•	Menopause\r\n•	Uterine abnormalities\r\n•	Certain medical conditions, such as Cushing\'s syndrome or pituitary tumors', 'The treatment of missed or late periods depends on the underlying cause. In cases where pregnancy is the cause, a woman may not require any treatment, and the period will return once the pregnancy ends. For other underlying medical conditions, the treatment may involve medications or surgical intervention.\r\n\r\nIn cases where stress or excessive exercise is the cause, lifestyle changes, such as practicing stress-reducing techniques or decreasing the intensity of physical activity, can help regulate the menstrual cycle. Women with eating disorders may require specialized treatment for their condition.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult a healthcare provider if you experience missed or late periods, especially if it is a recurring occurrence, to determine the underlying cause and receive appropriate treatment.'),
(114, 'Morning joint stiffness', 'Morning joint stiffness refers to the feeling of stiffness or limited range of motion that one may experience in their joints upon waking up in the morning. It is a common complaint among people of all ages, but is more frequently reported by older adults or those with certain medical conditions.', '•	Aging\r\n•	Arthritis, such as osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis or psoriatic arthritis\r\n•	Inflammatory disorders, such as lupus or ankylosing spondylitis\r\n•	Overuse injuries or previous joint injuries\r\n•	Prolonged inactivity or lack of movement\r\n•	Other medical conditions, such as fibromyalgia, hypothyroidism, or diabetes', '•	Gentle exercise or stretching before bed and in the morning\r\n•	Application of heat or cold therapy to affected areas\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain relief medications such as acetaminophen or ibuprofen\r\n•	Prescription medication for underlying conditions\r\n•	Physical therapy or occupational therapy\r\n•	Surgery, in severe cases where joint damage is extensive\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult with a healthcare professional if morning joint stiffness is persistent or if it significantly affects daily activities.'),
(115, 'Mouth sores', 'Mouth sores, also known as oral ulcers or stomatitis, are painful sores that can form in the mouth, on the lips, tongue, gums, or inside the cheeks. They can be red, swollen, and may have a white or yellow center. Mouth sores can be caused by a variety of factors such as viral infections, autoimmune diseases, medications, nutritional deficiencies, or physical trauma to the mouth.', '•	Viral infections such as cold sores (herpes simplex virus), chickenpox (varicella-zoster virus), or hand-foot-and-mouth disease (coxsackievirus).\r\n•	Bacterial infections such as strep throat (Group A streptococcus).\r\n•	Fungal infections such as oral thrush (Candida albicans).\r\n•	Autoimmune diseases such as lupus or Behçet\'s disease.\r\n•	Nutritional deficiencies such as vitamin B12, iron, or folic acid deficiency.\r\n•	Physical trauma to the mouth such as biting the inside of the cheek or burning the mouth with hot food or drinks.\r\n•	Certain medications such as chemotherapy drugs, antibiotics, or medications that suppress the immune system.', 'The treatment of mouth sores depends on the underlying cause. Mild cases of mouth sores may resolve on their own within a week or two. However, in severe cases or cases that persist, medical attention may be necessary. Treatments may include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter medications such as topical anesthetics or oral rinses to relieve pain and inflammation.\r\n•	Prescription medications such as antiviral or antifungal medications, corticosteroids, or immunosuppressants.\r\n•	Nutritional supplements or changes in diet to address any nutritional deficiencies.\r\n•	Lifestyle changes such as avoiding spicy or acidic foods, practicing good oral hygiene, and avoiding tobacco and alcohol.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if mouth sores persist for more than two weeks, are accompanied by a high fever or difficulty swallowing, or if they reoccur frequently.'),
(116, 'Muscle cramps', 'Muscle cramps refer to a sudden, involuntary, and painful contraction of one or more muscles. Cramps can last anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes and can occur at any time of the day, but they are more common at night. Muscle cramps can affect any part of the body, but they most commonly occur in the legs and feet.', '•	Dehydration\r\n•	Muscle fatigue or overuse\r\n•	Electrolyte imbalances (such as low levels of potassium, calcium or magnesium)\r\n•	Poor blood circulation\r\n•	Nerve compression or damage\r\n•	Medications (such as diuretics, steroids or statins)\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Underlying medical conditions (such as kidney disease, thyroid problems, or diabetes)', 'The treatment of muscle cramps depends on the underlying cause. Some ways to alleviate muscle cramps include:\r\n\r\n•	Stretching: Gently stretching the affected muscle may help to relieve the cramp.\r\n•	Massage: Massaging the cramped muscle can help to relax it.\r\nHeat or cold therapy: Applying heat or cold to the affected area can help to reduce pain and inflammation.\r\n•	Hydration: Drinking plenty of fluids can help to prevent dehydration and the risk of muscle cramps.\r\n•	Electrolyte replacement: If the cramps are caused by an electrolyte imbalance, replacing the missing electrolyte can help to alleviate the symptoms.\r\n•	Medications: Over-the-counter pain relievers such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen may help to alleviate pain caused by muscle cramps.\r\n\r\nIn most cases, muscle cramps are not serious and can be treated at home. However, if you experience severe or persistent muscle cramps, or if they are accompanied by other symptoms, such as swelling, redness, or weakness, it is important to consult with your healthcare provider.'),
(117, 'Muscle pain', 'Muscle pain, also known as myalgia, is a common condition that can occur in anyone, regardless of age or gender. It is usually characterized by discomfort, tenderness, or soreness in the muscles, which can be caused by various factors such as injury, overuse, or a medical condition.', '•	Overuse or injury: Straining the muscles by lifting heavy objects or performing repetitive movements can lead to muscle pain or injury. Similarly, playing sports, running, or participating in other physical activities can also cause muscle soreness or injury.\r\n•	Infection: Some viral or bacterial infections, such as the flu, Lyme disease, or malaria, can cause muscle pain and weakness.\r\n•	Autoimmune disorders: Certain autoimmune disorders like lupus or rheumatoid arthritis can cause muscle pain, as they attack the body\'s own tissues and muscles.\r\n•	Medications: Some medications like statins used to lower cholesterol levels, ACE inhibitors used to treat high blood pressure, or chemotherapy drugs used to treat cancer can cause muscle pain as a side effect.\r\n•	Metabolic disorders: Disorders like hypothyroidism or hyperthyroidism, which affect the thyroid gland, or diabetes, which affects blood sugar levels, can cause muscle pain.\r\n•	Fibromyalgia: A chronic disorder that causes widespread pain, fatigue, and tenderness in the muscles, ligaments, and tendons.\r\n•	Stress and anxiety: Prolonged stress or anxiety can cause muscle tension and pain.', 'The treatment of muscle pain depends on the underlying cause. Some general measures that can help relieve muscle pain include:\r\n\r\n•	Rest: Resting the affected muscle can help reduce inflammation and promote healing.\r\n•	Ice or heat therapy: Applying ice or heat to the affected area can help reduce pain and inflammation.\r\n•	Stretching: Gentle stretching exercises can help improve flexibility and relieve muscle tension.\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain medications: Medications like acetaminophen or nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) can help relieve pain and reduce inflammation.\r\n•	Massage: Massage therapy can help improve blood flow to the affected muscle, reduce muscle tension, and relieve pain.\r\n•	Physical therapy: A physical therapist can help develop an exercise program to strengthen the affected muscles and improve flexibility.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, medical treatment may be necessary, such as in the case of infections or autoimmune disorders. If you experience severe or persistent muscle pain, it\'s important to consult a healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.'),
(118, 'Muscle stiffness', 'Muscle stiffness refers to the sensation of tension, stiffness, or inflexibility in the muscles, particularly after a prolonged period of inactivity, like sleeping or sitting in the same position for a long time. It can occur in any muscle in the body and can vary in severity and duration.', '•	Overuse of muscles during physical activity or exercise\r\n•	Poor posture or holding the body in an awkward position for an extended period\r\n•	Injury to the muscles, tendons, or ligaments\r\n•	Medical conditions such as fibromyalgia, multiple sclerosis, and rheumatoid arthritis\r\n•	Certain medications, including some cholesterol-lowering drugs and blood pressure medications', 'Treatment for muscle stiffness depends on the underlying cause. Some general treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Rest: Taking a break from physical activity or prolonged sitting can help reduce muscle stiffness.\r\n•	Stretching: Gentle stretching exercises can help relieve muscle stiffness and improve flexibility.\r\n•	Heat or cold therapy: Applying heat or cold to the affected area can help reduce pain and stiffness.\r\n•	Massage therapy: Massage can help reduce muscle stiffness by improving blood flow and releasing tension.\r\n•	Over-the-counter pain relievers: Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) like ibuprofen can help reduce pain and inflammation.\r\n\r\nIf muscle stiffness is accompanied by other symptoms such as fever, weakness, or numbness, or if it persists for a long time and does not improve with self-care measures, it is recommended to consult a healthcare provider.'),
(119, 'Muscle twitching', 'Muscle twitching, also known as fasciculations, refers to involuntary muscle contractions that can occur in any muscle in the body. Twitching can be a minor inconvenience or can be a sign of a more serious underlying condition. Understanding the causes, symptoms, and treatment options for muscle twitching can help you identify the underlying cause and find the right treatment.', '•	Stress and anxiety\r\n•	Caffeine consumption\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Lack of sleep\r\n•	Side effects of medications\r\n•	Muscle fatigue\r\n•	Electrolyte imbalances\r\n•	Neurological disorders such as ALS, MS, and Parkinson\'s disease\r\n•	Nerve damage\r\n•	Muscle disorders such as muscular dystrophy and myasthenia gravis', 'The treatment of muscle twitching depends on the underlying cause. Some possible treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Stress reduction techniques such as meditation or deep breathing exercises\r\n•	Avoiding caffeine and increasing water intake to reduce dehydration\r\n•	Getting enough sleep\r\n•	Adjusting medications that may be causing muscle twitching\r\n•	Correcting electrolyte imbalances\r\n•	Treating underlying neurological or muscle disorders\r\n\r\nIn some cases, muscle twitching may not require any treatment and may go away on its own. However, if the twitching persists or is accompanied by other symptoms, it is important to consult with a healthcare provider to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.'),
(120, 'Nasal congestion', 'Nasal congestion, also known as a stuffy nose, is a common condition that occurs when the tissues and blood vessels in the nasal passages become swollen and inflamed. This can make it difficult to breathe through the nose, which can cause discomfort and interfere with daily activities.', '•	Allergies: An allergic reaction to pollen, dust mites, animal dander, or other allergens can cause nasal congestion.\r\n\r\n•	Infections: Viral or bacterial infections such as the common cold, flu, sinusitis, and pneumonia can cause inflammation of the nasal passages.\r\n\r\n•	Environmental irritants: Exposure to irritants such as cigarette smoke, pollution, and strong odors can cause nasal congestion.\r\n\r\n•	Structural problems: Structural problems in the nasal passages, such as a deviated septum or nasal polyps, can cause chronic nasal congestion.\r\n\r\n•	Hormonal changes: Hormonal changes during pregnancy, menstruation, or menopause can cause nasal congestion.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Certain medications such as birth control pills, blood pressure medications, and some antidepressants can cause nasal congestion as a side effect.', 'Treatment for nasal congestion depends on the underlying cause. Over-the-counter decongestants such as pseudoephedrine or phenylephrine can help relieve nasal congestion, but should not be used for more than a few days as they can cause rebound congestion. Saline nasal sprays or rinses can also help clear out mucus and reduce inflammation.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, prescription nasal sprays or oral medications may be necessary to treat underlying allergies or infections. If structural problems are the cause of the congestion, surgery may be necessary to correct the issue.\r\n\r\nTo prevent nasal congestion, avoid exposure to irritants such as cigarette smoke and air pollution, practice good hygiene by washing hands frequently, and stay hydrated by drinking plenty of fluids.'),
(121, 'Nausea', 'Nausea is a feeling of discomfort in the stomach that often precedes vomiting. It is a common symptom that can be caused by many different factors, ranging from simple indigestion to more serious underlying medical conditions.', '•	Gastrointestinal disorders, such as acid reflux, gastritis, and stomach ulcers\r\n•	Food poisoning or viral gastroenteritis\r\n•	Medications, such as antibiotics or chemotherapy drugs\r\n•	Pregnancy or hormonal changes\r\n•	Motion sickness or vertigo\r\n•	Anxiety or stress\r\n•	Migraine headaches\r\n•	Liver or kidney disease', 'The treatment for nausea depends on the underlying cause. In cases of mild nausea, home remedies such as sipping ginger tea or using acupressure bands may be effective. Over-the-counter medications such as antacids or anti-nausea drugs may also provide relief. If nausea is severe or accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever or abdominal pain, it is important to seek medical attention. Treatment may involve addressing the underlying medical condition or providing intravenous fluids and medications to manage symptoms.'),
(122, 'Neck pain', 'Neck pain is a common condition that affects many people at some point in their lives. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including injury, poor posture, degenerative changes in the cervical spine, and more.\r\n\r\nThe neck is made up of vertebrae that extend from the skull to the upper torso, with cervical discs that absorb shock between the bones. The muscles, bones, and ligaments of the neck support the head and allow for motion. Any abnormalities, inflammation, or injury can cause neck pain or stiffness.', '•	Poor posture\r\n•	Muscle strain or sprain\r\n•	Whiplash\r\n•	Osteoarthritis\r\n•	Degenerative disc disease\r\n•	Herniated or bulging disc\r\n•	Pinched nerve\r\n•	Spinal stenosis\r\n•	Infections or tumors (less common)', 'Neck pain can be mild or severe, and may be accompanied by other symptoms such as headaches, shoulder pain, or arm numbness. Treatment for neck pain depends on the underlying cause and may include rest, physical therapy, medication, heat or ice therapy, or in severe cases, surgery.\r\n\r\nIn general, maintaining good posture, stretching regularly, and engaging in regular exercise can help prevent neck pain from occurring. If you experience persistent or severe neck pain, it\'s important to seek medical attention to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.'),
(123, 'Night sweats', 'Night sweats refer to excessive sweating during sleep that is unrelated to the surrounding temperature. It can occur in men and women of any age and can be a symptom of an underlying medical condition or simply a result of external factors such as anxiety or stress.', '•	Menopause: Night sweats are a common symptom of menopause, which occurs in women when their estrogen levels decrease.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Some medications such as antidepressants, blood pressure medications, and steroids can cause night sweats as a side effect.\r\n\r\n•	Infections: Night sweats can be a symptom of various infections such as tuberculosis, HIV, and endocarditis.\r\n\r\n•	Hormonal imbalances: Night sweats can be caused by hormonal imbalances such as an overactive thyroid gland (hyperthyroidism) or an underactive thyroid gland (hypothyroidism).\r\n\r\n•	Anxiety and stress: Stress and anxiety can cause night sweats due to the body\'s natural fight or flight response.\r\n\r\n•	Cancer: Night sweats can be a symptom of certain types of cancer, including lymphoma and leukemia.', 'Treatment for night sweats depends on the underlying cause. If night sweats are caused by an underlying medical condition, treating that condition is usually the first step. For example, if night sweats are caused by an infection, treating the infection with antibiotics or antiviral medication may alleviate the night sweats.\r\n\r\nIf night sweats are a result of external factors such as anxiety or stress, taking steps to manage these factors can help reduce the frequency and severity of night sweats. This can include practicing relaxation techniques such as meditation, yoga, or deep breathing exercises.\r\n\r\nIn summary, night sweats can be a symptom of an underlying medical condition or simply a result of external factors such as anxiety or stress. Treatment depends on the underlying cause, and managing external factors can help reduce the frequency and severity of night sweats.'),
(124, 'Nipple pain', 'Nipple pain is a common complaint among women, and it can range from mild discomfort to severe pain. The pain can be caused by a number of factors, including breastfeeding, menstrual cycle, pregnancy, injury, or infection. In some cases, nipple pain may be a sign of a more serious underlying condition.', '•	Breastfeeding \r\n•	Infections like thrush\r\n•	Menstrual cycle\r\n•	Breast infection\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Hormonal changes\r\n•	Injury to the nipple\r\n•	Surgery', 'Treatment for nipple pain depends on the underlying cause. For breastfeeding-related pain, adjusting the baby\'s latch and using nipple creams or shields can help. For menstrual-related pain, over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen or acetaminophen may be recommended. In some cases, prescription medications may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIf the pain is due to an infection, antibiotics may be prescribed. In rare cases, nipple pain may be a sign of breast cancer, in which case, a biopsy may be needed. It\'s important to talk to a healthcare provider if nipple pain is severe or accompanied by other symptoms.'),
(125, 'Nosebleed', 'A nosebleed, also known as epistaxis, is the loss of blood from the tissue lining the nose. It is a common condition that can be caused by a variety of factors, ranging from mild to severe.', 'Nosebleeds can occur spontaneously or as a result of an injury to the nose. They can also be caused by dry air, high altitudes, allergies, certain medications, and medical conditions such as hypertension, blood clotting disorders, and tumors.', 'Treatment for nosebleeds typically involves applying pressure to the nose to stop the bleeding, using a saline nasal spray to keep the nasal passages moist, and avoiding blowing the nose for a period of time. In more severe cases, medical intervention may be necessary, such as cauterizing the blood vessels in the nose or packing the nose with gauze.\r\n\r\nPreventing nosebleeds can involve avoiding triggers such as dry air, using a humidifier to keep the air moist, and avoiding picking the nose or blowing the nose too forcefully. It is also important to manage any underlying medical conditions that may be causing nosebleeds.'),
(126, 'Pain during erection', 'Pain during erection can be caused by a variety of factors.', 'It could be a result of a physical injury or trauma to the penis, an infection, Peyronie\'s disease (a condition that causes the penis to curve), priapism (a prolonged and painful erection), or certain medications. Psychological factors such as anxiety, stress, or relationship problems can also cause pain during erections.', 'If you are experiencing pain during erection, it is recommended to see a healthcare provider for proper evaluation and treatment.'),
(127, 'Pain during urination', 'Pain during urination can be a sign of a urinary tract infection (UTI), which occurs when bacteria enters the urinary tract.', 'Other possible causes of pain during urination include sexually transmitted infections, kidney stones, and prostate problems.', 'It\'s important to see a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment, as untreated UTIs and other conditions can lead to serious complications.'),
(128, 'Penile pain', 'Penile pain can be caused by a variety of factors, including infections, injury, inflammation, or nerve damage. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience persistent or severe penile pain, as it may be a sign of a serious underlying condition. ', '•	Peyronie\'s disease: a condition where scar tissue builds up inside the penis, causing it to curve and leading to pain and difficulty with erections.\r\n•	Balanitis: inflammation of the foreskin and head of the penis, often caused by poor hygiene or a bacterial or fungal infection.\r\n•	Prostatitis: inflammation of the prostate gland, which can cause pain and discomfort in the penis, testicles, and lower abdomen.\r\n•	Epididymitis: inflammation of the epididymis, a coiled tube behind the testicles, which can cause pain and swelling in the scrotum and penis.\r\n•	Urinary tract infection: an infection in the urinary tract, which can cause pain and burning during urination, as well as pain in the penis and testicles.\r\n•	Injury: trauma to the penis, such as from a sports injury or accident, can cause pain and swelling.\r\n•	Nerve damage: damage to the nerves that control sensation in the penis can cause pain or numbness.', 'If you are experiencing penile pain, it is important to see a healthcare provider for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.'),
(129, 'Pale skin', 'Pale skin is a common symptom that may indicate an underlying health condition. This symptom is characterized by a loss of color in the skin, resulting in a pallor or whitening of the skin tone.', '•	Anemia\r\n•	Low blood pressure\r\n•	Shock\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Hypoglycemia\r\n•	Hypothyroidism\r\n•	Vitamin deficiency\r\n•	Raynaud\'s phenomenon\r\n•	Infection\r\n•	Malnutrition\r\n•	Chronic kidney disease', 'Treatment for pale skin depends on the underlying cause. A doctor will likely perform tests to determine the cause of the symptom, which may include blood tests, urine tests, or imaging studies. Treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Iron or vitamin supplements\r\n•	Blood transfusions\r\n•	Medications to treat underlying conditions, such as thyroid hormone replacement for hypothyroidism\r\n•	Intravenous fluids to treat dehydration or shock\r\n•	Antibiotics to treat infection\r\n•	Lifestyle changes, such as dietary modifications to address malnutrition\r\n\r\nIn some cases, pale skin may require emergency medical attention, particularly if it is accompanied by other symptoms such as dizziness, lightheadedness, or fainting. It is important to seek prompt medical attention if you are experiencing these symptoms.');
INSERT INTO `symptoms` (`symptom_id`, `symptom_name`, `description`, `causes`, `treatment`) VALUES
(130, 'Peeling skin', 'Peeling skin refers to the shedding of the outermost layer of skin, which is a natural process. However, when this shedding process is accelerated or excessive, it can lead to the appearance of peeling skin, which can be uncomfortable, unsightly, and potentially indicate an underlying condition.', '•	Dry skin\r\n•	Sunburn\r\n•	Irritation from chemicals or products\r\n•	Allergic reaction\r\n•	Infection (fungal, viral, or bacterial)\r\n•	Eczema\r\n•	Psoriasis\r\n•	Autoimmune disorders (such as lupus)\r\n•	Medications (such as retinoids or chemotherapy drugs)\r\n•	Genetic conditions (such as ichthyosis or epidermolysis bullosa)', 'Treatment for peeling skin will depend on the underlying cause:\r\n\r\n•	For dry skin, use a moisturizer regularly and avoid hot showers or baths\r\n•	For sunburn, use aloe vera gel or over-the-counter pain relievers\r\n•	For irritation from chemicals or products, discontinue use and avoid the offending substance\r\n•	For allergic reactions, use antihistamines or seek medical attention if severe\r\n•	For infections, treatment may include antibiotics or antifungal medications\r\n•	For eczema or psoriasis, use topical steroids or other prescription medications as directed by a healthcare provider\r\nFor autoimmune disorders, treatment may include immune-suppressing medications\r\n•	For medication-related peeling skin, talk to your healthcare provider about adjusting your medication regimen\r\n•	For genetic conditions, treatment is supportive and may include skin care and wound management.\r\n\r\nIf peeling skin is accompanied by other symptoms such as fever, pain, or swelling, it is important to seek medical attention promptly.'),
(131, 'Pelvic pain', 'Pelvic pain is a common symptom that can be experienced by both men and women. It refers to any pain or discomfort felt in the lower abdomen, pelvis, or groin area. Pelvic pain can range from mild to severe and may be acute or chronic. It can also be constant or intermittent, and it may be accompanied by other symptoms like fever, nausea, or vomiting.', '•	Gynecological conditions like ovarian cysts, endometriosis, or pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)\r\n•	Urinary tract infections or kidney stones\r\n•	Gastrointestinal conditions like irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) or inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)\r\n•	Musculoskeletal problems like pelvic floor dysfunction or hernias\r\n•	Reproductive system disorders like prostate problems or testicular torsion\r\n•	Nerve-related conditions like sciatica or pudendal neuralgia', 'The treatment for pelvic pain depends on the underlying cause. Some treatment options include:\r\n\r\n•	Antibiotics or other medications to treat infections or reduce inflammation\r\nHormone therapy or surgery for gynecological conditions like endometriosis or ovarian cysts\r\n•	Physical therapy to strengthen the pelvic muscles or improve alignment\r\n•	Surgery to repair hernias or other structural problems\r\n•	Pain management techniques like medications, nerve blocks, or acupuncture\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if you experience pelvic pain, especially if it is severe or accompanied by other symptoms. Your doctor can perform a physical exam, order tests or imaging studies, and recommend an appropriate course of treatment based on the underlying cause of your pain.'),
(132, 'Penile itching', 'Penile itching is a common condition that can be very uncomfortable and can cause embarrassment and frustration. It is characterized by itching, burning, or irritation in the area surrounding the penis. It can be caused by a number of factors, including skin conditions, infections, and allergies.', '•	Skin conditions: Certain skin conditions like psoriasis, eczema, and lichen planus can cause penile itching.\r\n\r\n•	Infections: Yeast infections, bacterial infections, and sexually transmitted infections (STIs) like herpes, chlamydia, and gonorrhea can all cause penile itching.\r\n\r\n•	Allergies: Contact dermatitis, which is an allergic reaction to certain substances like soaps, laundry detergents, and perfumes, can cause penile itching.\r\n\r\n•	Poor hygiene: Poor hygiene can lead to an accumulation of sweat and bacteria, which can cause penile itching.', '•	Topical creams: Antifungal or steroid creams can be prescribed by a doctor to treat penile itching caused by fungal infections or allergies.\r\n\r\n•	Antibiotics: If the itching is caused by a bacterial infection or STI, antibiotics can be prescribed.\r\n\r\n•	Hygiene: Good hygiene practices, such as keeping the area clean and dry, can help prevent penile itching.\r\n\r\n•	Lifestyle changes: Avoiding irritants and allergens that can cause penile itching can help prevent the condition from recurring.\r\n\r\n•	Medical intervention: If the itching is persistent or severe, a doctor may need to perform further testing to determine the underlying cause and prescribe appropriate treatment.\r\n\r\nPenile itching can be an uncomfortable and frustrating condition, but with proper treatment and prevention measures, it can be effectively managed. It is important to seek medical attention if the symptoms persist or worsen over time.'),
(133, 'Pounding heart', 'Pounding heart, also known as heart palpitations, is a sensation of your heart beating rapidly, irregularly, or forcefully. You may feel like your heart is fluttering, racing, or skipping beats. Pounding heart can be a normal response to physical activity, stress, or anxiety. However, it can also be a sign of an underlying medical condition that requires attention.', '•	Anxiety or panic attacks\r\n•	Physical activity\r\n•	Caffeine, alcohol, or nicotine use\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Anemia\r\n•	Hyperthyroidism\r\n•	Arrhythmia\r\n•	Heart disease or heart failure\r\n•	Medications or supplements', 'If you experience pounding heart accompanied by chest pain, shortness of breath, dizziness, or fainting, seek immediate medical attention.\r\n\r\nMedical treatments for pounding heart depend on the underlying cause. Your doctor may recommend lifestyle changes such as reducing caffeine intake, managing stress, and staying hydrated. If an underlying medical condition is diagnosed, treatment may include medications, surgery, or other interventions to correct the problem.\r\n\r\nIf you experience pounding heart frequently or are concerned about your symptoms, talk to your doctor. They can help determine the cause and provide appropriate treatment.'),
(134, 'Puffy eyelids', 'Puffy eyelids are a common condition that can be caused by a number of factors. They occur when there is swelling in the tissues around the eyes, making them appear swollen or larger than usual. While puffy eyelids are usually not a serious condition, they can be a sign of an underlying health issue.', '•	Allergies\r\n•	Lack of sleep\r\n•	Fluid retention\r\n•	Stress\r\n•	Aging\r\n•	Dermatitis\r\n•	Crying\r\n•	Sinus problems\r\n•	Infection', '•	Allergy medications or eye drops\r\n•	Warm compresses\r\n•	Cold compresses\r\n•	Over-the-counter creams or ointments\r\n•	Prescription medications\r\n•	Surgery (in rare cases)\r\n\r\nIt is important to speak with a healthcare professional if you have persistent or severe puffy eyelids, as it may be a sign of a more serious underlying condition.'),
(135, 'Rapid heart rate', 'Rapid heart rate, also known as tachycardia, is a condition characterized by a heart rate that exceeds the normal range. The normal range for heart rate is typically between 60 and 100 beats per minute, but a rapid heart rate is typically considered to be a heart rate that exceeds 100 beats per minute.', '•	Physical activity or exercise\r\n•	Anxiety or stress\r\n•	Fever\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Medications, such as asthma inhalers, beta-blockers, or thyroid medications\r\n•	Caffeine or other stimulants\r\n•	Heart conditions, such as atrial fibrillation, supraventricular tachycardia, or ventricular tachycardia', 'Treatment for rapid heart rate will depend on the underlying cause. In some cases, treatment may not be necessary if the rapid heart rate is due to physical activity or anxiety. However, if the rapid heart rate is due to an underlying medical condition, treatment may be necessary.\r\n\r\nMedical treatments for rapid heart rate may include:\r\n\r\n•	Medications, such as beta-blockers, calcium channel blockers, or anti-arrhythmic drugs\r\n•	Cardioversion, a procedure that uses electricity to restore a normal heart rhythm\r\n•	Ablation therapy, a procedure that uses heat or cold energy to destroy the heart tissue that is causing the abnormal heart rhythm\r\n•	Implantable devices, such as pacemakers or defibrillators, that can help regulate the heart rhythm'),
(136, '', 'Rectal bleeding refers to the presence of blood in the stool, which can appear bright red, maroon, or black and tarry in texture. This symptom can occur for a variety of reasons, ranging from minor conditions to more serious medical issues.', '•	Hemorrhoids: swollen and inflamed veins in the rectum or anus\r\n•	Anal fissures: small tears in the lining of the anus, often due to passing hard stools or diarrhea\r\n•	Diverticulitis: inflammation or infection of small pouches in the colon\r\n•	Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD): chronic inflammation of the digestive tract, including conditions like Crohn\'s disease and ulcerative colitis\r\n•	Colorectal polyps or cancer: growths in the colon or rectum that can be benign or malignant\r\n•	Rectal prolapse: a condition in which the rectum protrudes from the anus\r\n•	Gastrointestinal infections: bacterial or viral infections that can cause inflammation and bleeding in the digestive tract', 'Treatment for rectal bleeding will depend on the underlying cause. In some cases, self-care measures such as eating a high-fiber diet and staying hydrated can help alleviate symptoms. For more serious conditions like colorectal cancer, surgery or chemotherapy may be necessary. It is important to speak with a healthcare provider if you experience rectal bleeding, as early detection and treatment can lead to better outcomes.'),
(137, 'Red bloodshot eyes', 'Red bloodshot eyes, also known as conjunctivitis or pink eye, is a common condition that affects the outer layer of the eye and the inner surface of the eyelids. This condition causes the blood vessels in the eye to become inflamed, making the eyes appear red or pink in color.', '•	Viral or bacterial infection\r\n•	Allergies to dust, pollen, or other irritants\r\n•	Dry eyes\r\n•	Eye strain\r\n•	Injuries to the eye\r\n•	Contact lens use\r\n•	Chemical irritants', 'Treatment for red bloodshot eyes depends on the underlying cause. Some general treatments that may help relieve symptoms include:\r\n\r\n•	Applying a warm compress to the affected eye\r\n•	Using artificial tears to lubricate the eyes\r\n•	Avoiding allergens or irritants\r\n•	Taking over-the-counter antihistamines or decongestants (if allergies are the cause)\r\n•	Avoiding contact lens use until symptoms improve\r\n•	Using prescription eye drops or ointments (if infection is the cause)\r\n•	Seeking medical attention for more severe cases or if symptoms do not improve\r\n\r\nIn rare cases, red bloodshot eyes may be a symptom of a more serious condition, such as uveitis or glaucoma. If you experience severe or persistent symptoms, it is important to seek medical attention from an eye doctor.'),
(138, 'Red blood in stools', 'The presence of red blood in stools, also known as hematochezia, can be a cause for concern. It can be an indication of bleeding in the lower gastrointestinal tract, such as the rectum, colon or anus. The blood in the stool may be bright red, dark red, or maroon in color, depending on the site and amount of bleeding.', '•	Hemorrhoids\r\n•	Anal fissures\r\n•	Diverticulitis\r\n•	Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)\r\n•	Polyps or tumors in the colon or rectum\r\n•	Peptic ulcers\r\n•	Esophagitis\r\n•	Gastritis\r\n•	Intestinal infections\r\n•	Blood-thinning medications\r\n•	Radiation therapy', 'If you notice red blood in your stools, it is important to seek medical attention. Depending on the cause, treatment may include medications, dietary changes, or procedures such as colonoscopy or surgery.\r\n\r\nTreatment may include:\r\n\r\n•	Topical creams or ointments for hemorrhoids or anal fissures\r\n•	Antibiotics or antiviral medication for intestinal infections\r\n•	Medications to manage inflammatory bowel disease\r\n•	Surgery to remove polyps, tumors, or damaged tissue\r\n•	Changes to diet and lifestyle habits, such as increasing fiber intake or avoiding trigger foods\r\n•	Medication adjustments or changes to manage bleeding caused by blood-thinning medications\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention promptly to determine the underlying cause of the bleeding and ensure proper treatment.'),
(139, 'Red colored vomit', 'The presence of red colored vomit can be a concerning symptom and should be evaluated promptly by a medical professional. Vomiting of red-colored material may be caused by various factors', '•	Gastrointestinal bleeding: This can occur due to various causes, including ulcers, inflammation, tumors, or trauma in the digestive tract. When there is bleeding in the upper part of the digestive tract, the vomit may appear bright red in color. However, if the bleeding is in the lower part, the vomit may be mixed with darker colored blood.\r\n\r\n•	Ingestion of red-colored substances: Sometimes, the consumption of certain foods, beverages, or medications that are red in color can cause red vomit. For example, beets, cranberries, red candies, or red gelatin can give the vomit a red appearance.\r\n\r\n•	Red vomit can also be caused by other conditions such as infections, metabolic disorders, or certain types of cancer.\r\n\r\n', 'Treatment of red colored vomit depends on the underlying cause. In cases of gastrointestinal bleeding, immediate medical attention is required, and treatment may include blood transfusions, medications to stop the bleeding, or surgery. Ingestion of red-colored substances usually resolves on its own, but if symptoms persist or worsen, medical evaluation is necessary. It is important to seek medical attention promptly if red vomit is accompanied by other symptoms such as severe abdominal pain, fever, or difficulty breathing.'),
(140, 'Red gums', 'Red gums refer to gums that appear redder than usual, and may be accompanied by other symptoms such as swelling, bleeding, or tenderness.', '•	Gingivitis (inflammation of the gums)\r\n•	Periodontitis (inflammation and infection of the gums and surrounding tissues)\r\n•	Poor oral hygiene\r\n•	Vitamin deficiencies (particularly vitamin C)\r\n•	Hormonal changes during pregnancy\r\n•	Irritation or injury from dentures or braces\r\n•	Medications that cause gum irritation or bleeding', 'Treatment for red gums typically involves addressing the underlying cause:\r\n\r\n•	For gingivitis or periodontitis, treatment may include professional cleaning, scaling and root planing, antibiotics, and improved oral hygiene practices.\r\n•	Maintaining good oral hygiene practices, such as regular brushing and flossing, can also help prevent and treat red gums.\r\n•	In cases of vitamin deficiencies, supplements or dietary changes may be recommended.\r\n\r\nIf medications are causing gum irritation, a doctor may adjust the dosage or switch to a different medication.'),
(141, 'Red or black spots on the fingernails', 'The appearance of red or black spots on the fingernails can be concerning, and may indicate an underlying medical condition.', '•	Trauma or injury to the nail bed\r\n•	Fungal nail infection\r\n•	Bacterial infection\r\n•	Bleeding disorders\r\n•	Melanoma or other skin cancers\r\n•	Psoriasis or other skin conditions\r\n•	Medications or chemotherapy\r\n•	Vitamin or mineral deficiencies', 'The treatment for red or black spots on the nails will depend on the underlying cause of the symptom. Here are some potential treatment options:\r\n\r\n•	Trauma or injury: In some cases, the spot on the nail may simply be the result of an injury or trauma to the nail bed. If this is the case, the spot will typically grow out as the nail grows, and no treatment may be needed.\r\n•	Fungal infection: Treatment options for fungal nail infections may include antifungal medications or topical treatments.\r\n•	Bacterial infection: Antibiotics or other medications may be needed to treat a bacterial infection.\r\n•	Bleeding disorders: Treatment for bleeding disorders may include medications, transfusions, or other therapies to help control bleeding.\r\n•	Skin cancer: Depending on the type and severity of the cancer, treatment may involve surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or other options.\r\n•	Psoriasis or other skin conditions: Treatments for skin conditions may include topical or oral medications, light therapy, or other options.\r\n•	Vitamin or mineral deficiencies: If the spot on the nail is related to a vitamin or mineral deficiency, supplements or dietary changes may be recommended.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if you notice any changes or abnormalities in your nails, including the appearance of red or black spots. Your doctor can help determine the underlying cause of the symptom and recommend appropriate treatment options.'),
(142, 'Red spots', 'Red spots can appear on the skin for a variety of reasons. Some causes are harmless, while others can be more serious. Here is some information on the causes and treatment of red spots on the skin:\r\n\r\n', '•	Allergic reactions\r\n•	Infections such as chickenpox, measles, or shingles\r\n•	Insect bites or stings\r\n•	Contact dermatitis\r\n•	Psoriasis\r\n•	Eczema\r\n•	Rosacea\r\n•	Angiomas\r\n•	Hemangiomas\r\n•	Cherry angiomas\r\n•	Petechiae\r\n•	Purpura\r\n•	Hives\r\n•	Heat rash\r\n•	Folliculitis\r\n•	Razor burn\r\n•	Sunburn\r\n•	Medications\r\n•	Skin cancer', 'Treatment for red spots on the skin depends on the underlying cause. Mild cases may not require any treatment and may go away on their own. In other cases, treatment may be necessary to relieve symptoms and prevent complications. Some possible treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter creams or ointments to relieve itching or irritation\r\n•	Topical or oral medications for infections or inflammatory conditions\r\n•	Moisturizers to soothe dry or itchy skin\r\n•	Ice or cool compresses for swelling or pain\r\n•	Avoiding triggers that cause allergic reactions or contact dermatitis\r\n•	Sun protection to prevent sunburn or sun damage\r\n•	Surgical removal for skin cancers or growths that are causing symptoms or are at risk of becoming cancerous\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if you have red spots on your skin that are painful, bleeding, growing in size, or changing in shape or color. Your doctor can determine the underlying cause and provide appropriate treatment.'),
(143, 'Red tongue', 'A red tongue is a condition where the tongue appears redder than usual or has a bright red or strawberry color. While a red tongue can be caused by a variety of factors, it is usually not a cause for concern unless it is accompanied by other symptoms.', '•	Vitamin deficiencies, particularly vitamin B12 and folic acid\r\n•	Oral thrush or yeast infection in the mouth\r\n•	Scarlet fever, a bacterial infection that can cause a red, bumpy rash\r\n•	Kawasaki disease, a rare childhood illness that can cause inflammation in the blood vessels\r\n•	Geographic tongue, a harmless condition where the tongue appears to have a map-like pattern\r\n•	Dehydration or dry mouth\r\n•	Certain medications, such as antibiotics or blood pressure medications\r\n\r\nIn some cases, a red tongue may be a sign of an underlying medical condition, such as anemia or oral cancer.', 'Treatment for a red tongue will depend on the underlying cause. For example, if the redness is caused by a vitamin deficiency, increasing intake of vitamin B12 and folic acid through diet or supplements may help. If it is caused by a yeast infection, antifungal medications may be necessary. In more severe cases, medical treatment may be necessary to address underlying medical conditions.\r\n\r\nIt is important to speak with a healthcare provider if a red tongue is accompanied by other symptoms or is persistent.'),
(144, 'Ringing in the ears', 'Ringing in the ears, also known as tinnitus, is a condition where a person hears sound without an external source of sound. The sound can be described as ringing, buzzing, hissing, whistling, or clicking. Tinnitus can be temporary or chronic and can affect one or both ears.', '•	Exposure to loud noise\r\n•	Age-related hearing loss\r\n•	Earwax buildup\r\n•	Ear infections\r\n•	Meniere\'s disease\r\n•	Head or neck injuries\r\n•	High blood pressure\r\n•	Medications, such as antibiotics, antidepressants, and aspirin\r\n•	Tumors', '•	Treating the underlying cause, such as earwax removal, treatment of an infection, or discontinuing medication that may be causing tinnitus\r\n•	White noise machines or hearing aids to mask the sound\r\n•	Cognitive behavioral therapy to help manage the emotional distress associated with tinnitus\r\n•	Tinnitus retraining therapy to habituate the brain to the sound and reduce its perception\r\n•	Medications, such as antianxiety drugs, antidepressants, or anticonvulsants, to help alleviate symptoms.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult with a healthcare provider to determine the underlying cause of tinnitus and the most appropriate treatment.'),
(145, 'Runny nose', 'Runny nose, also known as rhinorrhea, is a condition where there is an excessive discharge of clear, thin, and watery mucus from the nose. It is a common symptom of a variety of conditions, ranging from allergies and colds to sinus infections and more serious conditions.', '•	Allergies: An allergic reaction to environmental irritants, such as dust, pollen, or pet dander, can cause a runny nose.\r\n\r\n•	Common cold: A viral infection that causes inflammation of the nasal passages and throat can result in a runny nose.\r\n\r\n•	Sinusitis: Inflammation of the sinuses can cause mucus buildup, leading to a runny nose.\r\n\r\n•	Rhinitis: An inflammation of the mucous membrane lining the nose can cause a runny nose.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Certain medicat•	e as a side effect.\r\n\r\n•	Hormonal changes: Changes in hormone levels during pregnancy or menopause can cause a runny nose.', '•	Nasal irrigation: Flushing out the nasal passages with a saline solution can help clear mucus and reduce inflammation.\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter medications: Antihistamines and decongestants can help relieve a runny nose caused by allergies or a cold.\r\n\r\n•	Prescription medications: If the underlying cause is a sinus infection, antibiotics or other prescription medications may be necessary.\r\n\r\n•	Humidifier: Using a humidifier can help keep the nasal passages moist and reduce irritation.\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding triggers: If the cause is an allergy, avoiding triggers such as pollen, dust, or pet dander can help prevent a runny nose.'),
(146, 'Sensitivity to light', 'Sensitivity to light, also known as photophobia, is a condition where an individual experiences discomfort or pain in the eyes when exposed to light. This can be caused by various factors, ranging from eye strain to serious medical conditions.', '•	Migraine headaches\r\n•	Concussion or other head injuries\r\n•	Eye infections or injuries\r\n•	Medications that increase light sensitivity as a side effect\r\n•	Corneal abrasions or scratches\r\n•	Inflammation of the iris (iritis)\r\n•	Glaucoma\r\n•	Albinism\r\n•	Cataracts\r\n•	Retinal detachment\r\n•	Blepharospasm (involuntary eyelid twitching)\r\n•	Brain tumors or lesions\r\n•	Withdrawal from certain medications', 'The treatment of sensitivity to light depends on the underlying cause. If the cause is a minor injury or infection, the sensitivity may subside on its own. In other cases, treatment may include:\r\n\r\n•	Wearing protective eyewear, such as sunglasses or special tinted lenses\r\n•	Medications, such as topical or oral anti-inflammatory drugs or corticosteroids\r\n•	Eye drops to help with inflammation\r\n•	Avoiding triggers that can cause migraines or headaches\r\n•	Surgery in severe cases, such as for cataracts or retinal detachment\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing sensitivity to light, it is important to see a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment.'),
(147, 'Shaking hands', 'Shaking hands, also known as hand tremors, is the involuntary shaking or trembling of the hand or fingers. Hand tremors are common and can occur at any age, but they tend to become more common as people get older. While hand tremors can be a normal part of aging, they can also be a symptom of an underlying condition.', '•	Essential tremor: A neurological disorder that causes involuntary shaking or trembling, usually in the hands or arms, but can also affect the head, voice, or legs. Essential tremor is the most common cause of hand tremors, and it tends to run in families.\r\n•	Parkinson\'s disease: A progressive disorder of the nervous system that affects movement. Parkinson\'s disease can cause hand tremors, as well as muscle stiffness, slow movement, and difficulty with balance and coordination.\r\n•	Multiple sclerosis: A chronic disease that affects the central nervous system. Multiple sclerosis can cause a range of symptoms, including hand tremors.\r\n•	Hyperthyroidism: A condition in which the thyroid gland produces too much thyroid hormone. Hyperthyroidism can cause a range of symptoms, including hand tremors.\r\n•	Anxiety: Excessive worrying or fear can cause shaking hands.\r\nAlcohol withdrawal: People who have been drinking heavily for a long time may experience shaking hands when they stop drinking.', '•	Essential tremor: Medications such as beta blockers, anticonvulsants, and tranquilizers can help reduce hand tremors. In some cases, surgery may be recommended.\r\n•	Parkinson\'s disease: Medications such as levodopa can help reduce hand tremors. Deep brain stimulation (DBS) surgery may also be an option.\r\n•	Multiple sclerosis: Treatment for hand tremors caused by multiple sclerosis may include medications such as beta blockers or anticonvulsants.\r\n•	Hyperthyroidism: Treatment for hyperthyroidism may include medications, radioactive iodine therapy, or surgery.\r\n•	Anxiety: Treatment for anxiety may include therapy, medications, or both.\r\n•	Alcohol withdrawal: Shaking hands caused by alcohol withdrawal will typically improve on its own as the body detoxifies. In some cases, medications may be used to manage symptoms.\r\n\r\nIt\'s important to see a doctor if you have persistent hand tremors, as they can be a symptom of an underlying condition that requires treatment.'),
(148, 'Shortness of breath', 'Shortness of breath, also known as dyspnea, is a condition where a person experiences difficulty breathing or a feeling of being out of breath. It can range from mild to severe and can be caused by many different underlying conditions.', '•	Asthma\r\n•	Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\r\n•	Pneumonia\r\n•	Pulmonary embolism (a blood clot in the lung)\r\n•	Heart disease\r\n•	Anemia\r\n•	Anxiety or panic attacks\r\n•	Obesity\r\n•	Physical exertion\r\n•	Allergies', 'The treatment of shortness of breath depends on the underlying cause. For example, if the cause is asthma, inhalers or other medications may be prescribed. For heart disease or a pulmonary embolism, hospitalization and more intensive treatment may be required. In general, if a person experiences sudden or severe shortness of breath, they should seek medical attention immediately.\r\n\r\nIn addition to medical treatment, there are lifestyle changes that can help alleviate shortness of breath, such as quitting smoking, maintaining a healthy weight, and avoiding triggers that may cause breathing difficulties. Breathing exercises and relaxation techniques may also be helpful in managing shortness of breath.'),
(149, 'Shoulder pain', 'Shoulder pain can be a common symptom that many people experience at some point in their lives. It can be caused by a variety of factors, such as injury, strain, overuse, or certain medical conditions.', '•	Rotator cuff injury\r\n•	Frozen shoulder\r\n•	Tendinitis\r\n•	Bursitis\r\n•	Arthritis\r\n•	Impingement syndrome\r\n•	Fractures or dislocations\r\n•	Pinched nerves\r\n•	Referred pain from the neck or chest', '•	Rest and ice\r\n•	Physical therapy\r\n•	Pain relievers\r\n•	Corticosteroid injections\r\n•	Surgery (in severe cases)\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing shoulder pain that is severe or persistent, it is important to seek medical attention. Your doctor can help determine the underlying cause of your shoulder pain and recommend the appropriate treatment plan.'),
(150, 'Skin blister', 'A skin blister is a small, fluid-filled bump that forms on the skin. Blisters can occur anywhere on the body, but are most commonly found on the hands and feet. They can be caused by a number of factors, including friction, burns, insect bites, and certain medical conditions.', '•	Friction or pressure on the skin\r\n•	Burns from heat or chemicals\r\n•	Exposure to extreme cold or sunburn\r\n•	Insect bites or stings\r\n•	Allergic reactions\r\n•	Contact dermatitis\r\n•	Viral infections such as herpes simplex\r\n•	Autoimmune disorders such as pemphigus or bullous pemphigoid\r\n•	Genetic conditions such as epidermolysis bullosa\r\n', '•	For blisters caused by friction or pressure, the best treatment is to avoid the activity that caused the blister and allow it to heal on its own. If the blister is large or painful, a doctor may drain it and apply a sterile dressing to prevent infection.\r\n•	For blisters caused by burns, it\'s important to cool the affected area immediately with cool running water for at least 10 minutes. A doctor may prescribe antibiotics to prevent infection and pain medication to manage pain.\r\n•	For blisters caused by viral infections, antiviral medications may be prescribed to reduce the severity and duration of the outbreak.\r\nFor autoimmune disorders or genetic conditions, treatment may involve managing symptoms with medication and avoiding triggers that can cause blistering.\r\n\r\nIn general, it\'s important to keep blisters clean and dry to prevent infection. Covering the blister with a sterile dressing can help protect it while it heals. If the blister is large or painful, seek medical attention to prevent complications.'),
(151, 'Skin bumps ', 'Skin bumps refer to the small, raised areas of the skin that can appear in different shapes, sizes, and colors. They can be caused by various factors such as infections, allergic reactions, genetic predispositions, or skin diseases. The medical term for skin bumps is papules, and they can occur anywhere on the body.', '•	Infections: Skin bumps can be caused by bacterial, viral, or fungal infections. Common infections that cause skin bumps include folliculitis, warts, herpes, and shingles.\r\n\r\n•	Allergic reactions: Skin bumps can be a result of an allergic reaction to certain foods, medications, or substances that come in contact with the skin.\r\n\r\n•	Genetic predispositions: Some people are genetically prone to developing skin bumps such as moles, skin tags, and seborrheic keratoses.\r\n\r\n•	Skin diseases: Skin bumps can be a symptom of various skin diseases such as psoriasis, eczema, and acne.', '•	Topical creams and ointments: If the skin bumps are caused by an infection or skin disease, a doctor may prescribe topical creams and ointments to treat the underlying condition.\r\n\r\n•	Cryotherapy: Cryotherapy involves freezing the skin bumps with liquid nitrogen to destroy them.\r\n\r\n•	Laser therapy: Laser therapy can be used to treat certain types of skin bumps such as warts and seborrheic keratoses.\r\n\r\n•	Surgery: Skin bumps that are large or pose a risk of cancer may need to be surgically removed.\r\n\r\nIn some cases, skin bumps can be harmless and require no treatment. However, if you have concerns about any skin bumps or notice any changes in size, color, or shape, it is recommended to see a doctor for an evaluation.'),
(152, 'Slow heart rate', 'Slow heart rate, also known as bradycardia, is a condition where the heart beats fewer than 60 times per minute. Bradycardia can occur in people of all ages, from newborns to the elderly. In some cases, slow heart rate may be a normal and healthy condition, while in other cases it can be a sign of an underlying health condition that requires medical attention.', '•	Age-related changes to the heart\'s electrical system\r\n•	Certain medications, such as beta blockers and calcium channel blockers\r\n•	Underactive thyroid gland (hypothyroidism)\r\n•	Damage to the heart\'s electrical system from heart disease, heart attack, or heart surgery\r\n•	Sleep apnea\r\n•	Electrolyte imbalances, such as low potassium or magnesium levels\r\n•	Infections such as Lyme disease or Chagas disease\r\n•	Genetic conditions, such as sick sinus syndrome', 'Treatment for slow heart rate depends on the underlying cause. In some cases, no treatment is necessary. If a medication is causing the slow heart rate, a change in medication may be necessary. In cases where slow heart rate is caused by an underlying medical condition, treatment of that condition may help alleviate the slow heart rate. For more severe cases, a pacemaker may be necessary to regulate the heart rate. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms of slow heart rate, such as fatigue, dizziness, or fainting.'),
(153, 'Sneezing', 'Sneezing is a common reflex act of expelling air forcibly from the nose and mouth due to irritation in the nasal passages. It is a natural defense mechanism of the body to remove irritants, allergens, or viruses from the nasal passage. Sneezing can also be a symptom of certain medical conditions.', '•	Allergies (such as hay fever, pet dander, dust mites, or pollen)\r\n•	Viral infections (such as the common cold or flu)\r\n•	Bacterial infections (such as sinusitis)\r\n•	Environmental irritants (such as smoke, pollution, or strong odors)\r\n•	Nasal polyps\r\n•	Certain medications\r\n•	Temperature changes\r\n•	Certain foods or spices', 'Medical treatment for sneezing depends on the underlying cause. Some remedies that may help relieve sneezing include:\r\n\r\n•	Over-the-counter antihistamines or decongestants\r\n•	Nasal saline sprays or rinses\r\n•	Avoiding exposure to allergens or irritants\r\n•	Keeping the air in the room moist with a humidifier\r\n•	Drinking plenty of fluids to help thin out mucus\r\n\r\nIn some cases, medical intervention may be necessary to address underlying conditions causing sneezing, such as sinusitis or nasal polyps. If you have persistent sneezing or other accompanying symptoms, it is important to seek medical advice from a healthcare professional.'),
(154, '', 'Snoring is a common condition in which a person makes a loud sound while breathing during sleep. The sound is produced when the flow of air through the mouth and nose is partially blocked, causing the tissues in the throat to vibrate. Snoring can disrupt sleep and lead to fatigue, irritability, and other health problems.', '•	Obesity or excess weight\r\n•	Narrow airways due to a structural abnormality, such as a deviated septum or enlarged tonsils\r\n•	Alcohol consumption or sedative use\r\n•	Aging\r\n•	Sleeping on one\'s back\r\n•	Allergies or congestion\r\n•	Smoking\r\n', 'Treatment for snoring depends on the underlying cause and may include:\r\n\r\n•	Lifestyle changes, such as losing weight, avoiding alcohol and sedatives before bedtime, and changing sleep position\r\n•	Treating underlying conditions, such as allergies or congestion\r\nUsing a continuous positive airway pressure (CPAP) machine to keep airways open during sleep\r\n•	Surgery to remove excess tissue or correct structural abnormalities\r\n\r\nIf snoring is affecting your quality of life or causing health problems, it\'s important to talk to a healthcare provider for an evaluation and appropriate treatment.'),
(155, 'Sore throat', 'A sore throat is a common condition that occurs when the back of the throat becomes inflamed, swollen, or irritated. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including viral or bacterial infections, allergies, and environmental irritants. The main symptom of a sore throat is pain or discomfort in the throat area, which may be accompanied by other symptoms such as difficulty swallowing, hoarseness, and swollen glands in the neck.', '•	Viral infections (e.g., common cold, flu, mononucleosis)\r\n•	Bacterial infections (e.g., strep throat, tonsillitis)\r\n•	Allergies or environmental irritants (e.g., pollen, dust, smoke)\r\n•	Dry air or dehydration\r\n•	Acid reflux\r\n•	Tumors or growths in the throat', 'Treatment for sore throat depends on the underlying cause. Viral infections typically resolve on their own within a week or two, while bacterial infections can be treated with antibiotics. Other treatments may include pain relievers, throat lozenges, gargling with salt water, and increasing fluid intake. In cases where sore throat is caused by environmental irritants or acid reflux, avoiding the irritants or taking medication to reduce acid reflux symptoms may be helpful.'),
(156, 'Stomach cramps', 'Stomach cramps refer to discomfort or pain in the abdominal region that can vary in intensity and duration. This symptom can be caused by various factors, including digestive problems, menstrual cramps, or a more serious medical condition.', '•	Gastrointestinal infections (e.g., gastroenteritis, food poisoning)\r\n•	Inflammatory bowel diseases (e.g., Crohn\'s disease, ulcerative colitis)\r\n•	Irritable bowel syndrome (IBS)\r\n•	Acid reflux disease\r\n•	Menstrual cramps\r\n•	Endometriosis\r\n•	Ovarian cysts\r\n•	Ectopic pregnancy\r\n•	Appendicitis\r\n•	Kidney stones\r\n•	Gallstones\r\n•	Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)\r\n•	Diverticulitis\r\n•	Ulcers\r\n•	Cancer', 'Medical treatment for stomach cramps depends on the underlying cause. Some general remedies for mild stomach cramps may include rest, applying heat to the affected area, or over-the-counter medications like antacids, pain relievers, or antidiarrheals. In more severe cases, medical treatment may include antibiotics, surgery, or other medications prescribed by a doctor.\r\n\r\nIt\'s important to seek medical attention if stomach cramps are severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms like vomiting, diarrhea, fever, or blood in the stool. These could be signs of a more serious condition that requires prompt medical treatment.'),
(157, 'Testicular pain', 'Testicular pain refers to the discomfort or pain experienced in one or both testicles, which are the male reproductive glands located in the scrotum. Testicular pain can occur suddenly or gradually, and it may be accompanied by other symptoms such as swelling, redness, or a lump in the testicle.', '•	Injuries: Trauma or injury to the testicles can cause pain, swelling, or bruising.\r\n•	Infections: Infections of the testicles or epididymis (a coiled tube behind the testicle that stores and transports sperm) can cause pain, swelling, redness, and fever.\r\n•	Torsion: Testicular torsion occurs when the testicle twists around the spermatic cord, cutting off the blood supply to the testicle. This is a medical emergency that can cause severe pain, swelling, nausea, and vomiting.\r\n•	Hydrocele: A hydrocele occurs when fluid builds up in the sac surrounding the testicle, causing swelling and discomfort.\r\n•	Varicocele: A varicocele is a swelling of the veins that drain the testicle, and it can cause pain or discomfort.\r\n•	Testicular cancer: Testicular cancer can cause a painless lump in the testicle, but it can also cause pain, discomfort, or a heavy feeling in the scrotum.', 'Treatment for testicular pain depends on the underlying cause. Injuries may require rest and pain relief medication, while infections may require antibiotics. Testicular torsion is a medical emergency that requires immediate surgery to save the affected testicle. Hydroceles and varicoceles may require surgery to drain fluid or repair the affected veins. Testicular cancer may require surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy depending on the stage and type of cancer.\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider if you experience testicular pain, especially if it is severe, accompanied by fever or nausea, or lasts for more than a few days. Early detection and treatment of testicular cancer can greatly improve the chances of successful treatment.'),
(158, 'Thick saliva', 'Thick saliva, also known as xerostomia, is a condition where the mouth produces an insufficient amount of saliva or the saliva is thicker than normal. Saliva is essential for the digestion process as it helps break down food, neutralizes acids in the mouth, and protects against tooth decay and gum disease.', '•	Dehydration: Not drinking enough water can cause the body to become dehydrated and produce thick saliva.\r\n•	Side effect of medication: Certain medications, such as antihistamines, antidepressants, and blood pressure medications, can cause dry mouth and thick saliva.\r\n•	Mouth breathing: Breathing through the mouth instead of the nose can cause the mouth to dry out and produce thick saliva.\r\n•	Infections: Some infections, such as sinusitis or an infection in the salivary gland, can cause thick saliva.\r\n•	Medical conditions: Certain medical conditions, such as Sjogren\'s syndrome or diabetes, can cause thick saliva.', '•	Drinking more water: Staying hydrated by drinking water and avoiding drinks that can dehydrate the body, such as coffee, alcohol, and sugary drinks, can help thin out thick saliva.\r\n•	Medication changes: If thick saliva is a side effect of medication, changing or adjusting the medication can help alleviate the symptoms.\r\n•	Mouth breathing remedies: If mouth breathing is causing thick saliva, using nasal sprays or breathing strips can help keep the mouth moist.\r\n•	Saliva substitutes: Over-the-counter saliva substitutes, such as sprays or gels, can help moisten the mouth and thin out thick saliva.\r\n•	Treating underlying conditions: Treating underlying medical conditions, such as Sjogren\'s syndrome or diabetes, can help reduce symptoms of thick saliva.\r\n\r\nIt is important to talk to a doctor if thick saliva persists or if it is accompanied by other symptoms, such as difficulty swallowing or speaking, as it could be a sign of a more serious medical condition.'),
(159, 'Throat tightness', 'Throat tightness is a common sensation that many people experience, and it can be caused by a variety of factors. It can be described as feeling like there is a lump or tightness in the throat that makes it difficult to swallow or breathe.', '•	Anxiety or stress\r\n•	Allergies or allergic reactions\r\n•	Acid reflux\r\n•	Infections, such as tonsillitis or strep throat\r\n•	Smoking or exposure to secondhand smoke\r\n•	Vocal strain or overuse\r\n•	Thyroid issues, such as goiter or thyroiditis\r\n•	GERD (gastroesophageal reflux disease)', 'If you are experiencing throat tightness, it is important to speak with a medical professional to determine the underlying cause and develop a treatment plan. Some potential treatments may include:\r\n\r\n•	Managing anxiety or stress through therapy or relaxation techniques\r\n•	Avoiding allergens or taking allergy medication\r\n•	Taking medication to treat acid reflux or GERD\r\n•	Antibiotics to treat infections\r\n•	Voice therapy or rest to manage vocal strain\r\n•	Thyroid hormone medication to treat thyroid issues\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if you experience severe throat tightness, difficulty breathing, or chest pain, as these can be signs of a serious medical emergency.'),
(160, 'Upset stomach', 'Upset stomach is a common term used to describe various symptoms that affect the digestive system. This condition can be caused by a variety of factors, such as eating too much or too quickly, food poisoning, infections, stress, and certain medical conditions.', '•	Nausea\r\n•	Vomiting\r\n•	Abdominal pain or cramps\r\n•	Bloating\r\n•	Diarrhea or constipation\r\n•	Loss of appetite\r\n\r\nIn some cases, an upset stomach may be accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, headache, and body aches. Depending on the cause of the upset stomach, treatment options may vary. For mild cases, home remedies such as drinking plenty of fluids, eating smaller meals, avoiding spicy and fatty foods, and getting enough rest may be helpful. Over-the-counter medications such as antacids, anti-diarrheals, and pain relievers may also provide relief.', 'In more severe cases, medical treatment may be necessary. For example, if the upset stomach is caused by a bacterial infection, antibiotics may be prescribed. If the condition is caused by a more serious underlying medical condition, such as inflammatory bowel disease, additional medical interventions may be required.\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing symptoms of an upset stomach that persist for more than a few days or are accompanied by other concerning symptoms, it is important to seek medical attention.'),
(161, 'Vaginal bleeding', 'Vaginal bleeding can refer to any bleeding that occurs from the vagina, including menstrual bleeding, spotting, or bleeding during pregnancy. While some causes of vaginal bleeding are benign, others can be serious and require medical attention.', '•	Menstrual bleeding: Regular menstrual cycles cause bleeding that lasts for several days.\r\n•	Hormonal imbalances: Changes in hormone levels can cause irregular bleeding or spotting.\r\n•	Pregnancy complications: Bleeding during pregnancy can be a sign of a miscarriage, ectopic pregnancy, or other serious conditions.\r\n•	Infections or inflammation: Infections such as yeast infections or sexually transmitted infections can cause vaginal bleeding.\r\n•	Fibroids or polyps: These growths in the uterus or cervix can cause bleeding, especially after sex or during menopause.\r\n•	Cancer: Rarely, vaginal bleeding can be a sign of cervical or uterine cancer.', '•	Hormonal medications: Hormonal imbalances can be treated with medications that regulate hormone levels, such as birth control pills or hormone replacement therapy.\r\n•	Antibiotics: Infections can be treated with antibiotics.\r\n•	Surgery: Fibroids or polyps may require surgical removal.\r\n•	Blood transfusions: If bleeding is severe, a blood transfusion may be necessary.\r\n\r\nIf you experience vaginal bleeding, especially if it is heavy or accompanied by pain, it is important to seek medical attention to determine the underlying cause and appropriate treatment.'),
(162, 'Vaginal discharge', 'Vaginal discharge is a common symptom experienced by women. It is a fluid that is produced by the cervix and vagina and helps to keep the vaginal area clean and moist. Normal vaginal discharge can vary in color and consistency depending on the time of the menstrual cycle, and it can also change during pregnancy or menopause.', 'Abnormal vaginal discharge may be a sign of an infection or other health issue. The following are some possible causes of abnormal vaginal discharge:\r\n\r\n•	Bacterial vaginosis\r\n•	Yeast infection\r\n•	Sexually transmitted infections (STIs), such as chlamydia, gonorrhea, or trichomoniasis\r\n•	Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID)\r\n•	Cervical or vaginal cancer', 'Treatment for abnormal vaginal discharge depends on the underlying cause. Some possible treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Antibiotics to treat bacterial infections\r\n•	Antifungal medications to treat yeast infections\r\n•	Antiviral medications to treat viral infections\r\n•	Medications to treat STIs\r\n•	Surgery or other treatments for cancer\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider if you experience abnormal vaginal discharge, as some causes may require medical treatment.'),
(163, 'Vaginal dryness', 'Vaginal dryness refers to the discomfort and irritation caused by the reduction of natural lubrication in the vagina.', 'This condition is usually caused by a decrease in the production of estrogen, which can occur during menopause, breastfeeding, or after cancer treatments that affect the ovaries. Other causes of vaginal dryness include medications such as antihistamines and antidepressants, stress, anxiety, and autoimmune disorders.', 'Treatment for vaginal dryness may involve the use of vaginal moisturizers or lubricants to alleviate discomfort and reduce friction during sexual activity. Hormone therapy, such as estrogen replacement therapy or vaginal estrogen creams, may also be prescribed to increase vaginal lubrication and reduce symptoms.\r\n\r\nIt is important to consult with a healthcare provider if you experience persistent vaginal dryness or discomfort, as it may be a sign of an underlying medical condition that requires treatment. Additionally, practicing good genital hygiene and avoiding harsh soaps or douches may help prevent vaginal dryness and irritation.');
