(164, 'Vaginal itching', 'Vaginal itching is an uncomfortable and often distressing symptom that can occur in women of all ages. It is a common problem and can be caused by a variety of factors. Vaginal itching can be accompanied by other symptoms such as redness, swelling, burning, or soreness. It can be acute or chronic and can vary in intensity.', '•	Yeast infection: An overgrowth of yeast in the vagina can cause itching, burning, and discharge.\r\n\r\n•	Bacterial vaginosis: An imbalance in the bacteria that normally inhabit the vagina can cause itching, discharge, and a foul odor.\r\n\r\n•	Trichomoniasis: This is a sexually transmitted infection that can cause itching, discharge, and a foul odor.\r\n\r\n•	Irritation: Anything that irritates the delicate skin of the vagina can cause itching, including scented soaps, bubble baths, and certain types of laundry detergent.\r\n\r\n•	Menopause: The decrease in estrogen that occurs during menopause can cause vaginal dryness and itching.', '•	Over-the-counter antifungal creams: These creams can be used to treat yeast infections.\r\n\r\n•	Prescription medications: If the cause of the itching is a bacterial infection or a sexually transmitted infection, prescription medications may be necessary.\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding irritants: Avoiding products that irritate the skin of the vagina can help reduce itching.\r\n\r\n•	Hormone therapy: If the itching is caused by menopause, hormone therapy may be helpful.\r\n\r\n•	Home remedies: There are a variety of home remedies that can be used to relieve itching, including applying cold compresses, taking a baking soda bath, or using apple cider vinegar. However, it is important to talk to a healthcare provider before using any home remedy to ensure it is safe and effective.'),
(165, 'Vaginal odor ', 'Vaginal odor is a common issue that many women experience. While it is normal for the vagina to have a natural odor, a strong or unpleasant smell can indicate an underlying issue.', '•	Bacterial vaginosis: This is a common condition that occurs when there is an overgrowth of bacteria in the vagina. Symptoms include a fishy odor, white or gray discharge, and itching.\r\n\r\n•	Yeast infections: Yeast infections can also cause an unpleasant odor, along with itching, burning, and a thick, white discharge.\r\n\r\n•	Trichomoniasis: This is a sexually transmitted infection that can cause a strong, unpleasant odor, along with itching, burning, and a yellow-green discharge.\r\n\r\n•	Poor hygiene: Not washing the vaginal area regularly can cause a buildup of sweat and bacteria, leading to an unpleasant odor.\r\n\r\n•	Hormonal changes: Changes in hormone levels, such as during pregnancy or menopause, can affect the natural balance of bacteria in the vagina, leading to an odor.', '•	Antibiotics: Bacterial vaginosis and trichomoniasis are both treated with antibiotics. Your doctor will prescribe the appropriate medication based on your symptoms and test results.\r\n\r\n•	Antifungal medication: Yeast infections are treated with antifungal medication, either as a pill, cream, or suppository.\r\n\r\n•	Maintaining good hygiene: Regularly washing the vaginal area with mild soap and warm water can help reduce unpleasant odors. Avoid using scented products or douching, as these can disrupt the natural balance of bacteria in the vagina.\r\n\r\n•	Hormone therapy: If hormonal changes are causing the odor, your doctor may recommend hormone therapy to balance your hormone levels.\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider if you are experiencing an unpleasant vaginal odor, as it can be a sign of an underlying condition that needs to be treated.'),
(166, 'Vaginal pain', 'Vaginal pain can be a distressing and uncomfortable experience for women. It can be caused by various factors such as infections, trauma, or conditions that affect the reproductive organs. In some cases, it may also be related to psychological factors such as stress and anxiety.', '•	Infections: vaginal pain is often caused by infections such as yeast infections, bacterial vaginosis, and sexually transmitted infections (STIs) such as herpes, chlamydia, or gonorrhea.\r\n\r\n•	Trauma: trauma to the vaginal area can cause pain during sexual intercourse or other activities. This can include childbirth, surgery, or injury.\r\n\r\n•	Vaginal dryness: vaginal dryness can occur due to hormonal changes or as a side effect of medication. This can cause pain during sexual intercourse or other activities.\r\n\r\n•	Gynecological conditions: certain gynecological conditions such as endometriosis, ovarian cysts, or fibroids can cause vaginal pain.\r\n\r\n•	Psychological factors: psychological factors such as stress, anxiety, or depression can cause vaginal pain by increasing muscle tension or interfering with sexual arousal.', 'The treatment for vaginal pain depends on the underlying cause. Some common treatments include:\r\n\r\n•	Antibiotics: antibiotics may be prescribed to treat bacterial infections such as bacterial vaginosis or STIs.\r\n\r\n•	Antifungal medication: antifungal medication may be prescribed to treat yeast infections.\r\n\r\n•	Hormone therapy: hormone therapy may be used to treat vaginal dryness caused by hormonal changes.\r\n\r\n•	Surgery: surgery may be necessary to treat conditions such as endometriosis, ovarian cysts, or fibroids.\r\n\r\n•	Counseling or therapy: counseling or therapy may be recommended to address psychological factors that may be contributing to vaginal pain.\r\n\r\nIn addition to medical treatment, there are also some self-care measures that can help alleviate vaginal pain, such as:\r\n\r\n•	Avoiding irritants: avoiding irritants such as scented products or harsh soaps can help reduce vaginal pain.\r\n\r\n•	Lubrication: using a water-based lubricant can help reduce pain during sexual intercourse.\r\n\r\n•	Relaxation techniques: relaxation techniques such as deep breathing or meditation can help reduce muscle tension and alleviate vaginal pain.\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing vaginal pain, it is important to see a healthcare provider to determine the underlying cause and receive appropriate treatment.'),
(167, 'Vomiting', 'Vomiting, also known as emesis, is the act of forcefully expelling the contents of the stomach through the mouth. It is a common symptom that can occur due to a wide range of causes, including infections, food poisoning, motion sickness, pregnancy, medication side effects, and underlying medical conditions.', '•	Viral or bacterial infections, such as stomach flu or gastroenteritis\r\n•	Food poisoning or food allergies\r\n•	Motion sickness\r\n•	Overeating or consuming large amounts of alcohol\r\n•	Medication side effects or reactions\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Gastrointestinal conditions, such as inflammatory bowel disease or gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)\r\n•	Neurological conditions, such as migraines or brain tumors\r\n•	Endocrine disorders, such as diabetes or thyroid disorders\r\n•	Psychological conditions, such as anxiety or bulimia', 'Treatment for vomiting will depend on the underlying cause. In most cases, vomiting is not a serious medical issue and will resolve on its own within a few days. However, in some cases, it may be necessary to seek medical attention. Treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Resting and avoiding solid foods until vomiting stops\r\n•	Drinking clear fluids or electrolyte-replacement drinks to prevent dehydration\r\n•	Taking over-the-counter medications, such as antihistamines or antiemetics, to alleviate symptoms\r\n•	Prescription medications to treat underlying medical conditions\r\n•	Hospitalization for severe cases, such as dehydration or complications from an underlying medical condition\r\n\r\nIf vomiting persists for more than a few days or is accompanied by other symptoms, such as fever, severe abdominal pain, or blood in the vomit, it is important to seek medical attention promptly.'),
(168, 'Vomiting blood', 'Vomiting blood, also known as hematemesis, is a medical emergency that can be caused by a variety of conditions. It occurs when there is bleeding in the upper gastrointestinal tract, typically in the stomach or esophagus, and the blood is then vomited up.', '•	Peptic ulcers: These are sores that develop in the lining of the stomach or small intestine, often caused by the bacteria H. pylori or long-term use of nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs).\r\n\r\n•	Esophageal varices: These are enlarged veins in the esophagus that can burst and cause severe bleeding, usually as a complication of liver disease.\r\n\r\n•	Mallory-Weiss tear: This is a tear in the lining of the esophagus that can be caused by vomiting, coughing, or severe retching.\r\n\r\n•	Gastritis: This is inflammation of the stomach lining, often caused by H. pylori, excessive alcohol consumption, or prolonged use of NSAIDs.\r\n\r\n•	Cancer: Certain types of cancer, such as stomach or esophageal cancer, can cause bleeding in the upper gastrointestinal tract.', 'Medical treatment for vomiting blood depends on the underlying cause and severity of the bleeding. It may involve hospitalization, blood transfusions, endoscopy to stop the bleeding, and medications to treat the underlying condition.\r\n\r\nIf you or someone you know is experiencing vomiting blood, it is important to seek emergency medical attention immediately.'),
(169, 'Watery eyes', 'Watery eyes, also known as epiphora, is a common condition where tears overflow from the eyes, causing excessive tearing. It can occur in one or both eyes and may be accompanied by other symptoms like redness, irritation, and blurred vision.', '•	Allergies: Allergic reactions to dust, pollen, or pet dander can cause watery eyes.\r\n\r\n•	Dry eyes: When the eyes do not produce enough tears, the body may respond by producing excessive tears to compensate, causing watery eyes.\r\n\r\n•	Eye infections: Infections such as conjunctivitis or pink eye can cause watery eyes along with other symptoms such as redness and discharge.\r\n\r\n•	Blocked tear ducts: When the tear ducts become blocked, tears cannot drain properly, causing them to overflow.\r\n\r\n•	Eye irritation: Exposure to irritants such as smoke, wind, or bright lights can cause watery eyes.\r\n\r\n•	Eyelid problems: Malfunctioning eyelids or eyelashes can cause the eyes to become excessively dry or tearful.\r\n\r\n•	Medical conditions: Certain medical conditions like Bell\'s palsy, Sjogren\'s syndrome, or thyroid disorders can cause watery eyes.', '•	Over-the-counter eye drops: Artificial tears or other lubricating eye drops can help reduce dryness and irritation.\r\n\r\n•	Allergy medications: Antihistamines or other allergy medications can help control allergic reactions.\r\n\r\n•	Warm compresses: Applying a warm compress to the eyes can help relieve inflammation and improve tear production.\r\n\r\n•	Surgery: In some cases, surgery may be needed to treat a blocked tear duct or other underlying condition causing watery eyes.\r\n\r\n•	It\'s important to see an eye doctor if you experience persistent or severe watery eyes, as it may be a sign of an underlying condition that requires treatment.'),
(170, 'Watery mouth', 'A watery mouth, also known as hypersalivation or sialorrhea, is a condition where there is an excessive production of saliva in the mouth. It is a normal response to the stimulation of taste or smell, but can also be a symptom of an underlying condition.', '•	Medications\r\n•	Reflux disease\r\n•	Infections, such as strep throat or tonsillitis\r\n•	Neurological disorders, such as Parkinson\'s disease or cerebral palsy\r\n•	Oral conditions, such as gum disease or mouth ulcers\r\n•	Anxiety or stress\r\n•	Pregnancy\r\n•	Mouth breathing\r\n•	Dehydration\r\n•	Poisoning or exposure to toxins', 'The treatment of watery mouth depends on the underlying cause. Some possible treatment options include:\r\n\r\n•	Medication adjustments or changes\r\n•	Treating underlying infections with antibiotics\r\n•	Botox injections to reduce salivary gland activity\r\n•	Mouthwash or other oral care products to reduce oral bacteria and plaque\r\n•	Behavioral therapy or relaxation techniques to manage anxiety or stress\r\n•	Surgery to remove or block salivary glands in severe cases\r\n\r\nIf you are experiencing watery mouth along with other symptoms such as difficulty swallowing, difficulty breathing, or fever, seek medical attention immediately as it may be a sign of a more serious underlying condition.'),
(171, 'Wheezing', 'Wheezing is a high-pitched whistling sound that occurs when air flows through narrowed or constricted airways. It is often associated with breathing difficulties and can be a symptom of various medical conditions, including respiratory infections, allergies, asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and heart failure.', '•	Asthma\r\n•	Bronchiolitis\r\n•	Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\r\n•	Emphysema\r\n•	Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)\r\n•	Heart failure\r\n•	Infections such as pneumonia and bronchitis\r\n•	Inhalation of a foreign object\r\n•	Lung cancer\r\n•	Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV)\r\n•	Smoking or exposure to secondhand smoke', '•	Bronchodilators: These medications work to relax the muscles around the airways, making it easier to breathe.\r\n•	Steroids: These medications work to reduce inflammation in the airways, helping to decrease wheezing and improve breathing.\r\n•	Oxygen therapy: In cases of severe wheezing or breathing difficulty, supplemental oxygen may be necessary to maintain adequate oxygen levels in the blood.\r\n•	Allergy medications: If allergies are causing the wheezing, antihistamines or allergy shots may be prescribed.\r\n•	Lifestyle changes: Quitting smoking, avoiding exposure to environmental irritants, and maintaining a healthy weight can all help to reduce wheezing and improve breathing.\r\n\r\nIt is important to seek medical attention if wheezing is severe, persistent, or accompanied by other symptoms such as chest pain, rapid breathing, or bluish skin.'),
(172, 'White tongue', 'White tongue, also known as coated tongue, is a condition where the surface of the tongue appears white or yellowish due to the presence of debris, bacteria, and dead cells. While a healthy tongue is typically pink and covered in small nodules, a white tongue can indicate a variety of health problems or issues with oral hygiene.', '•	Poor oral hygiene\r\n•	Dry mouth or dehydration\r\n•	Mouth breathing\r\n•	Smoking or tobacco use\r\n•	Yeast infections such as thrush\r\n•	Medications, such as antibiotics or steroids\r\n•	Immune system disorders\r\n•	Nutrient deficiencies, such as iron or vitamin B12', 'Treatment for white tongue depends on the underlying cause. Improving oral hygiene by brushing the tongue or using a tongue scraper can help remove debris and bacteria. Maintaining adequate hydration and avoiding tobacco use can also improve symptoms. In cases where white tongue is caused by a fungal infection, antifungal medications may be prescribed. If a nutrient deficiency is the cause, supplementation or dietary changes may be recommended.\r\n\r\nIf you experience persistent white tongue or other symptoms, it is important to consult a healthcare professional for an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.'),
(173, 'Wrist pain', 'Wrist pain is a common condition that affects people of all ages. It can be caused by a variety of factors, such as repetitive motions, injury, or arthritis. In some cases, wrist pain can be a sign of an underlying medical condition, such as carpal tunnel syndrome or tendinitis.', '•	Repetitive motion injuries: This is a common cause of wrist pain, particularly in people who perform repetitive tasks with their hands and wrists, such as typing or playing an instrument.\r\n\r\n•	Arthritis: Osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis can both cause wrist pain. Osteoarthritis occurs when the cartilage in the wrist joint wears down, while rheumatoid arthritis is an autoimmune disorder that causes inflammation in the joint.\r\n\r\n•	Carpal tunnel syndrome: This is a condition that occurs when the median nerve in the wrist is compressed. It can cause pain, numbness, and tingling in the wrist and hand.\r\n\r\n•	Tendinitis: This is an inflammation of the tendons in the wrist, which can cause pain and swelling.\r\n\r\n•	Sprains and strains: A sprain occurs when the ligaments in the wrist are stretched or torn, while a strain occurs when the muscles or tendons are stretched or torn.', '•	Rest: It is important to rest the affected wrist to allow it time to heal. This may involve taking a break from certain activities that may be causing the pain.\r\n\r\n•	Ice and heat therapy: Applying ice or heat to the affected area can help reduce inflammation and alleviate pain.\r\n\r\n•	Medications: Over-the-counter pain relievers, such as ibuprofen or acetaminophen, can help reduce pain and inflammation.\r\n\r\n•	Physical therapy: In some cases, physical therapy may be recommended to help improve strength and flexibility in the wrist.\r\n\r\n•	Surgery: In severe cases, surgery may be required to correct the underlying problem causing the wrist pain.\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a doctor if wrist pain is severe, persistent, or interfering with daily activities. They can perform a physical exam, diagnose the underlying cause of the pain, and recommend an appropriate treatment plan.'),
(174, 'Yellow eyes', 'Yellowing of the eyes, also known as scleral icterus, is a medical condition where the white part of the eyes (sclera) appears yellow or orange. This yellowing is caused by the accumulation of bilirubin, a yellow pigment produced by the liver, in the blood and tissues of the body.', '•	Liver disease or damage, such as cirrhosis, hepatitis, or liver cancer\r\n•	Hemolytic anemia, a condition where the body destroys red blood cells too quickly, leading to an increase in bilirubin\r\n•	Gilbert\'s syndrome, a genetic condition that affects the liver\'s ability to process bilirubin\r\n•	Pancreatic cancer\r\n•	Gallstones or other issues with the gallbladder\r\n•	Certain medications, such as acetaminophen and some antibiotics\r\n•	Alcohol abuse', 'The underlying cause of yellow eyes must be treated to reverse the condition. Treatment options may include:\r\n\r\n•	Medications to treat liver or gallbladder conditions\r\n•	Blood transfusions in cases of severe hemolytic anemia\r\n•	Surgery to remove gallstones or treat other issues with the gallbladder\r\n•	Changes in diet or medication to address alcohol abuse\r\n•	Chemotherapy or radiation therapy for pancreatic cancer\r\n\r\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider promptly if you notice yellowing of the eyes or other symptoms of liver or gallbladder issues. Delaying treatment can lead to more serious complications.');
